commit_message:
Rename service client classes which include "Ip"

FloatingIPsClient and FixedIPsClient classes contain "IP" which means
"Internet Protocol" in their names, but FloatingIpPoolsClient and
FloatingIPsBulkClient contain "Ip" as the same meaning.
To make class names consistent, this patch renames later classes for
including "IP" instead.

Partially implements blueprint consistent-service-method-names

Change-Id: Ia16e8d29ac3972bf3c46bb9af07ca3f94c576620

Add a description of a token parameter to :

- all API of managing domains except for "POST /v3/domains"

commit_message:
Add a token to a request parameter of API managing groups

Add a description of a token parameter to :
- all API of managing groups except for "GET /v3/groups"
- all API of managing domains except for "POST /v3/domains"
- all API of managing credentials except for "GET /v3/credentials".
- "GET /v3/roles" and "GET /v3/role_assignments".

For details, please see http://developer.openstack.org/api-ref-identity-v3.html#groups-v3.

Change-Id: Ib6f4d2237962207cecc55fa8daea626b8ff80199
Closes-Bug: #1478527

commit_message:
Run a nodepool devstack test

sdague has kindly written a devstack plugin to run nodepool against
devstack. With that in place we can start testing that nodepool runs
against a real cloud. Start running this test.

Change-Id: I27ad3f135cf517972b4f02775983cdc74ac3d694

commit_message:
Updates to delete service method in (os-services) extension

The correct URI is: /v2/{tenant_id}/os-services/{service_id}
The correct normal response codes is 204

Remove tabs as notices by niceness check

Change-Id: I5d176780b094e36f891b452bd2c0bae2e20a6e97
Closes-Bug: 1478429

commit_message:
keystone/auth: make service description configurable

This commit adds the service description (service_description) and service
description for S3 (service_description_s3) as a class parameter in order
to allowusers to update from a previous version if the service description
is changed (incorrectly spelled or wrong description).

Change-Id: I5b52ce2fb89c9e0c4e9470c676b35da249f89bbe
Closes-Bug: #1468407

commit_message:
keystone/auth: make service description configurable

This commit adds the service description as a class parameter in order to allow
users to update from a previous version if the service description is changed
(incorrectly spelled or wrong description)

Change-Id: Ifa39ae38c1004924f14089cfc45394839d442081
Closes-Bug: #1468407

commit_message:
keystone/auth: make service description configurable

This commit adds the service description as a class parameter in order to allow
users to update from a previous version if the service description is changed
(incorrectly spelled or wrong description)

Change-Id: I86dcdb118a229cfdf7b0cde8010eb26b71a0ab32
Closes-Bug: #1468407

I'm wondering if this isn't satisfied by the documentation effort that Tim is leading."}, {'account_id': 11716, 'date': '2015-07-29 14:05:22.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

One of the main goals of the docs work is to provide a comprehensive list of all plugins and options. So, yes this duplicates on that, however it does not hurt to have the info in a few places, incase people don't RTFM. 

I do wonder if this will become deprecated when we fix our config situation though?"}, {'account_id': 11861, 'date': '2015-07-29 14:06:37.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2

I like this, most projects go through and comment Keystone's profile.  Would be good if they could start from all plugins.  My only concern is that we'll need to remember to keep it fresh.

And yeah, to Tim's point, we'll probably have to move these around, but... in the meantime it's a good change IMO."}, {'account_id': 11716, 'date': '2015-07-29 14:09:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 8119, 'date': '2015-07-29 14:23:07.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

To the previous points, I do think this is more of s stop-gap until the documentation and the config changes are improved.  I do think it'll be useful in the meantime.  

Technically, the list of plugins can be seen in the setup.cfg also.  I should probably add a test that ensures the All profile indeed has all of the plugins by comparing with stevedore's loaded extensions."}, {'account_id': 979, 'date': '2015-07-29 22:19:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

Whilst I hate to see the config file grow further, this feels like a really good user centric change.

When the config situation is solved, this feels like something that should be handled in code rather than config.

But, for the time being - this is a massive +1.

Thanks'}, {'account_id': 6486, 'date': '2015-07-30 02:07:32.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

(2 comments)

I don't think this is useful. A link to the docs would be."}, {'account_id': 8119, 'date': '2015-07-30 17:16:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

(1 comment)

@Brant - even with docs, it's kinda a pain to copy and paste each plugin name into bandit.yaml from another link.  This is just here for convenience and a stop-gap measure.  Ultimately, I would prefer not to have any profile  information in bandit.yaml at all."}, {'account_id': 6486, 'date': '2015-07-30 22:24:32.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

[{'created': '2015-07-29 05:21:54.000000000', 'message': "Add all available plugins to an example profile

One of the pain points in using bandit is knowing what are all of
the available plugins such that they can be included or excluded
as according to the project.

This patch creates a new default profile to bandit.yaml called 'All'
which includes all bandit plugin options.

Change-Id: I8772cf40045eb5b7ef270086ea5988282d220f3b
"}]
commit_message:
Add all available plugins to an example profile

One of the pain points in using bandit is knowing what are all of
the available plugins such that they can be included or excluded
as according to the project.

This patch creates a new default profile to bandit.yaml called 'All'
which includes all bandit plugin options.

Change-Id: I8772cf40045eb5b7ef270086ea5988282d220f3b

[{'created': '2015-07-13 12:33:22.000000000', 'message': 'Convergence: Fix for resource needed_by

When resources are replaced, the needed_by needes to be updated. When
the resources are visited in clean-up phase - after all the updates are
done - new needed_by data is sent to the resources.

Change-Id: Ib3bff461ab4cdd43391c7fcdfff6d8eb17fe2555
Co-Authored-By: Rakesh HS  <rh-s@hp.com>

commit_message:
Convergence: Fix for resource needed_by

When resources are replaced, the needed_by needes to be updated. When
the resources are visited in clean-up phase - after all the updates are
done - new needed_by data is sent to the resources.

Change-Id: Ib3bff461ab4cdd43391c7fcdfff6d8eb17fe2555
Co-Authored-By: Rakesh HS  <rh-s@hp.com>

commit_message:
Introduce support for APC MasterSwitchPlus and Rack PDU

Provide 3 new snmp_driver values for different APC product families:
  - apc_masterswitch
  - apc_masterswitchplus
  - apc_rackpdu

The "apc" snmp_driver is still supported and maps to the MasterSwitch driver
to avoid breaking backwards compatibility.

Different APC product families support different OIDs for power control.
  - APC MasterSwitch uses sPDUOutletCtl
  - APC MasterSwitchPlus uses sPDUOutletControlMSPOutletCommand
  - APC Rack PDU uses rPDUOutletControlOutletCommand

Change-Id: I9d8724543d7da7b1c9cdc180c3396d131ed52615
Closes-Bug: #1471025

commit_message:
Fixing test_volume_boot_pattern when use_floatingip_for_ssh=false

It turns out that the "test_volume_boot_pattern" test doesn't
work if use_floatingip_for_ssh is false. To make this test working
the corresponding changes in the test were done.

Change-Id: I2a007ba46b7b93a8fb7aa70e52bced88383e5cd3
Closes-Bug: #1478482

Modify commonFaults ENTITY

commit_message:
Fix "List pools" response parameter descriptions

The following parameters are changed:
- "lb_algorithm" changes to "lb_method"
- "healthmonitor_id" changes to "health_monitors"
The following parameters descriptions are added:
- "subnet_id"
- "vip_id"
- "health_monitors_status"
- "provider"

Change-Id: I49b8f68628583750814f6b4ce8d913522b1a0e5e
Closes-bug: #1477874

commit_message:
Add Content-Range description for random access to images

New feature "API support for random access to images"
is described on "Image service API v2."
in the section of "Download binary image data"
  GET /v2/images/{image_id}/file

Change-Id: I12b945b6c43f83977e2916e355f598243ab23658
Closes-Bug: #1367074

following error:

  https://jenkins06.openstack.org/job/gate-puppet-heat-puppet-syntax-4-dsvm-centos7/1/consoleText

Closes-Bug: #1477354

commit_message:
Adding app.module.spec.js

This patch adds spec for app.module.js which has been missing since
it cannot be auto-collected to Jasmine test runner.

Added spec for the module's definition.  The run block is all about
configuring `horizon` object which is in old code and there is patch
moving them out off app.module.js since they are not really belong
to here, therefore specs for the code in the run block is not added.

Change-Id: I835eb6488ee5809ce874dbb7f5d34d06d0b5573d
Closes-Bug: #1480007

commit_message:
gnocchi: reduce the number of patch to gnocchi API

This refactor the processing of the samples to
more clearly separation the resource creation/update
and the measurements posting.

This refactor have permit to do only on PATCH of resource
per resource received into samples.

So, more samples are present in the received message more this code
is efficient.

Note, the workflow have changing, now resource are updated even
the posting of the measurements fail.

Change-Id: I01b758a13388da34636dc983a6c8c1550046d419

commit_message:
Add information 'node_uuid' in debug logs to facilitate the reader's life

Some people in other patch about info log level suggested that some
LOG.debug calls should also inform the 'node_uuid' on the log
message, so this patch addresses this suggestion.

Change-Id: I99bda6e6bf63c45f824f9ae1d92091abbd220d63

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-07-28 22:38:21.000000000', 'message': 'Add Nova scheduler_tracks_instance_changes config to docs

This option defaults to True and doesn't really make sense in an Ironic
context. It tracks instances by host in the scheduler, to allow for
better choosing of a host. However, Ironic only allows for one host, so
there's no opportunity to schedule to a host with more capacity.

Additionally, with the potential to have hundreds or thousands of
instances on a single "host" in Ironic, the get_by_host query this
config causes to run can completely knock over the scheduler.

Let's recommend turning it off. :)

Change-Id: I3c34dd8ef06a339606e56cd57d5b7d523dedc09b
'}]
commit_message:
Add Nova scheduler_tracks_instance_changes config to docs

This option defaults to True and doesn't really make sense in an Ironic
context. It tracks instances by host in the scheduler, to allow for
better choosing of a host. However, Ironic only allows for one host, so
there's no opportunity to schedule to a host with more capacity.

Additionally, with the potential to have hundreds or thousands of
instances on a single "host" in Ironic, the get_by_host query this
config causes to run can completely knock over the scheduler.

Let's recommend turning it off. :)

Change-Id: I3c34dd8ef06a339606e56cd57d5b7d523dedc09b

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC
    Workflow: http://docs.openstack.org/infra/manual/developers.html
    Commit Messages: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/GitCommitMessages"}, {'account_id': 12516, 'date': '2015-07-09 02:28:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

commit_message:
Report capability of multiattach for FlashSystem

This patch enables the multiattach capability reporting in
_update_volume_stats. This will allow nova to attach and detach
a volume to multiple virtual machine instances.

Change-Id: Ie66850c954168612dd1c17c14e75cd64c0c6d1e7
Implements: blueprint ibm-flashsystem-multiattach

[{'created': '2015-07-23 22:08:24.000000000', 'message': "Decouple amp driver from network using new models

The amphora driver's post_vip_plug method required network specific information
about the amphora to complete implementations.  It was not accepting anything
other than a loadbalancer object.  Now it takes a dictionary of
AmphoraNetworkConfig objects that is keyed of amphora id.  Each instance
contains network specific information required to set up the correct routing
on the amphora.

This patch sets up the routing correctly to solve the vip blackholing issue but

commit_message:
Decouple amp driver from network using new models

The amphora driver's post_vip_plug method required network specific information
about the amphora to complete implementations.  It was not accepting anything
other than a loadbalancer object.  Now it takes a dictionary of
AmphoraNetworkConfig objects that is keyed of amphora id.  Each instance
contains network specific information required to set up the correct routing
on the amphora.

This patch sets up the routing correctly to solve the vip blackholing issue but
only for the ssh_driver.  The argument has only been added to the post_vip_plug
method of the rest_api_driver but will need to be updated to handle this new
information and to also fix the vip blackholing problems.

Change-Id: I17ce89b6c050a2a36e0a802920e2dedb063f615b
Closes-Bug: #1453951

commit_message:
Remove the explicit chown root

This is not possible when running multihost ansible.
Essentially this should've been part of #1476293.

Change-Id: I53baccf5f89e71ce1313524815f928ea04908a05
Partitially-Implements: blueprint ansible-service

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 1390, 'date': '2015-07-27 15:47:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 10428, 'date': '2015-07-27 18:30:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

(3 comments)

Paul, thanks for actively playing with this already!

Please check out my comments.

About your SSH note, I've tried updating the docs to point out this is to be used as a contained dev environment: "When done, press destroy".
Plus the reasoning behind adding in ssh private keys from $USER (the user running Vagrant) was that at first I wanted to bridge to the outside network, where SSH access to the vagrant cluster would be required.. I simply hadn't worked out a proper networking plan/setup. At that time I didn't know about vagrant ssh either. I could end up removing the SSH-key bits, but at this point there is no attack surface; the Vagrant machines are only connected to a NAT-network and a host-only-network.'}, {'account_id': 1390, 'date': '2015-07-28 09:03:27.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

Wrt ssh keys, it's not so much security I'm worried about. It's more just an extra thing to go wrong to assume a user has those properly set up and available. Both myself and James tripped over this from the outset, me because I use ssh auth forwarding to a dev box and so had no keys, and James for similar reasons. So I'm not asking you to rip it all out, simply just it might be a good idea to run ssh-keygen and add those keys instead. It's not a huge deal to me so if it's hassle I won't press the matter!

The other thing that is more of an issue in my eyes is that the script can't be run twice. I totally get that this is a transient setup and meant to be thrown away frequently, the problem is they still take quite a while to create. By the time I've waited the hour or so to bootstrap 4 nodes and build+push kolla images on my operator, I really hate to throw it all away just to make a tweak in the provisioning script.

I've added a few patches already in my local area to workaround this, if you like I can push them here, or maybe better we can merge this and I'll propose them after the fact."}, {'account_id': 1390, 'date': '2015-07-28 09:18:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

commit_message:
Vagrantfile and docs

With Vagrant it becomes real easy to create a dev environment to
test and checkout $code. The focus is specifically on setting up
an environment to play around in, developing Kolla and showing
what it is capable of in a clean virtualised environment. When
done, the environment can be destroy and re-created at will when
needed.

Change-Id: I440d004e76c337f298cad2397cf4c13f2cc35ddb
Implements: blueprint vagrant-devenv

commit_message:
Environment inheritance for freezer agent executed by the scheduler

With this patch, when the scheduler execute the agent, the environment
is inherited. This would allow the scheduler to fully work with
virtual env

Change-Id: Ic382a3b0fdf1bb6a1bdfdce3dbbc025ed897f411

Temporary disable rally verify functional job

It is blocking gates. Until we find the way to fix it let's
turn it off

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-06-18 06:38:08.000000000', 'message': "Kill rsync/scp processes before deleting instance

In the resize operation, during copying files from source to
destination compute node scp/rsync processes are not aborted after
the instance is deleted because linux kernel doesn't delete instance
files physically until all processes using the file handle is closed
completely. Hence rsync/scp process keeps on running until it
transfers 100% of file data.

Added callback methods to execute call which will store the pid of
scp/rsync process in cache as a key: value pair and to remove the pid
from the cache after process completion. Process id will be used to
kill the process if it is running while deleting the instance. Instance
uuid is used as a key in the cache and pid will be the value.

SecurityImpact

Change-Id: Ie03acc00a7c904aec13c90ae6a53938d08e5e0c9
Closes-bug: #1387543
"}, {'created': '2015-06-23 06:45:16.000000000', 'message': "libvirt: Kill rsync/scp processes before deleting instance

In the resize operation, during copying files from source to
destination compute node scp/rsync processes are not aborted after
the instance is deleted because linux kernel doesn't delete instance
files physically until all processes using the file handle is closed
completely. Hence rsync/scp process keeps on running until it
transfers 100% of file data.

Added callback methods to execute call which will store the pid of
scp/rsync process in memorycache as a key: value pair and to remove the
pid from the cache after process completion. Process id will be used to
kill the process if it is running while deleting the instance. Instance
uuid is used as a key in the cache and pid will be the value.

SecurityImpact

Closes-bug: #1387543
Change-Id: Ie03acc00a7c904aec13c90ae6a53938d08e5e0c9

commit_message:
libvirt: Kill rsync/scp processes before deleting instance

In the resize operation, during copying files from source to
destination compute node scp/rsync processes are not aborted after
the instance is deleted because linux kernel doesn't delete instance
files physically until all processes using the file handle is closed
completely. Hence rsync/scp process keeps on running until it
transfers 100% of file data.

Added new module instancejobtracker to libvirt driver which will add,
remove or terminate the processes running against particular instances.
Added callback methods to execute call which will store the pid of
scp/rsync process in cache as a key: value pair and to remove the
pid from the cache after process completion. Process id will be used to
kill the process if it is running while deleting the instance. Instance
uuid is used as a key in the cache and pid will be the value.

SecurityImpact

Closes-bug: #1387543
Change-Id: Ie03acc00a7c904aec13c90ae6a53938d08e5e0c9

commit_message:
Move puppetlabs-stdlib to librarian

This change removes our copy of stdlib and replaces it with a version
managed via librarian-puppet-simple.

Partial blueprint: fuel-puppet-librarian

Change-Id: I16fd42f666cf142c5efc7362ed0a3b9bbcded249

commit_message:
Add description for flavor CPU topology parameters

The hw:cpu_sockets, hw:cpu_cores and hw:cpu_threads extra specs on
flavors are now included in the API reference. The max properties
are now correctly defined with _.

Closes-Bug: #1479270
Change-Id: I07159d4e542968ca51deae63173441f014e3afef
Signed-off-by: Tim Bell <tim.bell@cern.ch>

commit_message:
Adds guidance on request bodies with different Methods

Although HTTP technically allows bodies for almost all methods,
we should restrict to PUT and POST to align with what most people
actually think, including many client framework authors.

This follows ML discussion http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-May/063788.html

Change-Id: I16e857c7cb9d6fc0c80e6b2028571a41e990a694

commit_message:
Add openstack_user_domain to assertion

Currently, a keystone IdP does not provide the domain of the user
when generating SAML assertions. Since it is possible to have two
users with the same username but in different domains, this patch
adds an additional attribute called "openstack_user_domain"
in the assertion to identify the domain of the user.

Closes-Bug: 1442787
bp assertion-extra-attributes

Change-Id: I65d5c02c0a21f4d4c1b54f8aa56e27950d20badd
(cherry picked from commit ae2d7075ff58e426e324e2eac57c852ffd4bc804)

commit_message:
Provide base method for inspect_memory_resident

The inspect_memory_resident was introduced a few months back.  When a
new inspector element is added, it should also be added to the base
inspector.  The base inspector should raise a NotImplementedError.

Due to this missing defintion, the pollster for the resident memory was
throwing an error for every instance that was sampled - if that
inspector did not have this method defined.

This change set adds a base definition, which removes the excessive
logging per instance when using a non-libvirt inspector.

Change-Id: Ibac8a18a3e84fb90763c48c892583d8d3785c91c
Closes-Bug: 1480309

commit_message:
Raise HTTP exception for backup not found

If backup cannot be found while resetting its status, Cinder
exception (BackupNotFound) is raised instead of HTTP exception.
This patch handles the BackupNotFound exception and raises
HTTPNotFound exception.

APIImpact
HTTPNotFound exception (404) is raised instead of BackupNotFound
if backup cannot be found during backup reset-status.

Change-Id: I5a41c71a83c05d09c6d1e2e506adca6cfbe3e890
Closes-Bug: #1474748

[{'created': '2015-07-28 23:50:33.000000000', 'message': 'Configurable token hashing

Provide info on the option for operators to turn off token
hashing to be performed by horizon.

In some deployments where PKI token format is used for keystone,
token hashing causes 401 errors in horizon.

Relates to https://review.openstack.org/#/c/201360/

Change-Id: I5ebc07850b14b2f2f52fc659831d6cd4aa9f83c3
Closes-Bug: #1473588

commit_message:
Configurable token hashing

Provide info on the option for operators to turn off token
hashing to be performed by horizon.

In some deployments where PKI token format is used for keystone,
token hashing causes 401 errors in horizon.

Depends-On: I187b1486db2e453fd49298e1478e30abe97e54fe

Change-Id: I5ebc07850b14b2f2f52fc659831d6cd4aa9f83c3
Closes-Bug: #1473588

commit_message:
ceilometer: add tempest option to test events

event support in Ceilometer was implemented in Kilo. to enable
tests in tempest, we add an option to run tests only on Kilo+
branch.

Depends-On: I5ae2aa700ddd0c89255e07fe2f188d7742eb6406
Change-Id: Ia4a73b7df343e31e6301f8314490fd42a01b7cd0
(cherry picked from commit 71e4e6f601381494e640f424876bad0f92b6dc9b)

commit_message:
Allow Cinder to raise when attaching a volume

There's work[1] in Cinder that will result in a possibility to receive
VolumeIsBusy exception when calling Cinder's attach. This commit
increases Nova's error tolerance to gracefully handle such situations.

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/149894/
Partial-Bug: 1458958

Change-Id: I77d32688129125639b2064344a7f455e5d6375ee

i guess my main goal is to ensure tests run as normal but also validate that when an instance is created, measurement datapoints are generated AND an event datapoint is generated. the call to query event datapoint requires admin access currently which is why i needed to add admin client.

i'd ideally like this to be run all the time but i take it this is not possible?"}, {'account_id': 7350, 'date': '2015-06-24 08:41:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 12:

@Gordon, What David meant is Tempest is used also outside of the Gate, without devstack, to test "real" OpenStack installations. On these installations, the user that runs Tempest might not know the admin creds.

Because your new test requires the admin creds in telemetry/base.py, all Ceilo tests will now require the admin creds.

What I suggest, is you introduce a new class BaseTelemetryAdminTest(BaseTelemetryTest) and all the tests that require admin creds or a mix of non admin and admin creds inherit from this BaseTelemetryAdminTest class.'}, {'account_id': 6537, 'date': '2015-06-24 12:28:00.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 12:

commit_message:
add initial check for nova event in ceilometer

this patch adds the ability to query ceilometer events and includes
a check that nova events are recorded.

Change-Id: I5ae2aa700ddd0c89255e07fe2f188d7742eb6406

Fix Neutron cleanup

Fixes the cleaning up of Neutron resources by changing the
order of deleting leaf objects such as ports and subnets.

this patch refactors the Angular code for 'flavor' step

commit_message:
Fix pemutils for py34

pemutils tests were failing py34 with an error like:

 ...
   File "/opt/stack/keystone/keystone/tests/unit/common/test_pemutils.py", line 32, in make_base64_from_data
     return base64.b64encode(data)
   File "/opt/stack/keystone/.tox/py34/lib/python3.4/base64.py", line 62, in b64encode
     encoded = binascii.b2a_base64(s)[:-1]
 TypeError: 'str' does not support the buffer interface

bp python3

Change-Id: Ie3f259596e2610fe39f22352e9c07d5674277515

commit_message:
Fix broken agent virtual media drivers

This commit fixes the agent virtual media drivers
(agent_ilo, agent_irmc) which were broken due to
Ib6caa445cd577e295c89e908650b29f5823523ed. This is just
a workaround to avoid the problem.  The better fix for the
actual commit (Ib6caa445cd577e295c89e908650b29f5823523ed)
will happen when boot/deploy interfaces are separated.

Closes-Bug 1478459
Change-Id: I6a3e3ee4a2d57768b76a630ebcb5462ea8ec464c

From our irc chat, we could call self.update(db_snapshot) to update the fields of the object instead of returning the object after create, which would cause us to re-assign the object that was just initialized to the new object returned by create().

Another option is to add a refresh() method into each object, which would make a db call to update the object, but that would be an unnecessary db call.

    @base.remotable
    def refresh(self):
        current = self.__class__.get_by_id(self._context, self.id)

        for field in self.fields:
            # NOTE(thangp): Only update attributes that are already set.  We
            # do not want to unexpectedly trigger a lazy-load.
            if self.obj_attr_is_set(field):
                if self[field] != current[field]:
	            self[field] = current[field]
        self.obj_reset_changes()'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-07-09 17:46:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

commit_message:
Return object after create

After volume/snapshot/backup creation in the database
we convert DB model to object but don't return it. Thi
patch fixes this issue.

Change-Id: I12af68a8fa730bcd3aaec41be5c3f06e788b62a8

commit_message:
Stop specifying requirements.txt in tox.ini

As PBR already injects the contents of requirements.txt into
setup_requires, there is no need for tox to explicitly install them.

http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-July/069663.html

Change-Id: If8c254e32eeb969332140f380882940579ad474f

commit_message:
Accept string, None values in Python API

Python API is configured to only accept int and float valued metrics.
But agents sometimes send string values (which must be converted to
numeric) or None values.

Change-Id: I241597a5bfd09f4e8e6b36c4b0d4a91e66ad639f
Closes-Bug: 1414853

commit_message:
Fix docs for environment markers in extras

The docs for environment markers in setup.cfg [extras] had a
couple of issues.

1) There was a space after the package name.
2) python_environment was used where python_version is the marker.

Change-Id: Idbc72c45ae240356ca39eeba6db754f56c6a0f23

Change-Id: I8849dc5fb187c2278e99fe8c41322b5f2c139879

commit_message:
Activate pep8 check that _ is imported

Remove the specification in tox.ini that _ is a builtin so that
it will no longer assume that _ does not need to be imported.
This helps ensure that the _ from i18n is used.

Activating this check did not flag any violations.

Change-Id: I8849dc5fb187c2278e99fe8c41322b5f2c139879

Correct reference to deploy_image variable in install playbook

The install playbook was creating an incorrectly-named image.
Fix the reference to the variable so that the image is named
correctly.

commit_message:
Fix error handling in the exception module on py3

* Replace dict.iteritems() with dict.items() in code handling errors in
  the exception module to fix Python 3 support.
* Add new unit tests on the exception module

Change-Id: Ib958421dbdd73fb442e17a8d0654c9eab8b7b70e

commit_message:
Transform keystone::roles::admin Class into a Define

Transform the class that create admin resources into a define so we can
reuse the same code with different parameters in the same catalog.

It keeps 100% backward compatibility since keystone::roles::admin is now
consumming the new Define resource.
This patch also fix the case when admin_project_domain == admin_user_domain
and add unit tests to validate it works.

One of the use case is when we want to create admin resources for
Keystone v2 and v3 together.

Closes-bug: #1474049
Change-Id: Ia6b677e124d2b6aeea746238efe7d2a7629a30f1

commit_message:
Raise exception on failed lock's CM acquire fail

In lock's context manager we are not checking that acquire returns true
before entering managed code.

Even though we don't except acquire to return False, we should still
confirm that the lock has been really acquired and we can proceed, and
raise an exception if it failed.

This patch modified metaclass Lock to raise new exception
LockAcquireFailed if it didn't acquire the lock.

Change-Id: I6d6f14ffd9ea10dd1ca203a92c987334e8a00416

be retiring in the future.  Additionally, we move into centos7 to
avoid the hurt of other projects using devstack-trusty.

Since we are installing puppet from gems, we don't need to rely on the
OS as much. However, if we want to add a devstack-trusty node in the

commit_message:
Move puppet-syntax gate to devstack-centos7

The main reason is to move away from the bare nodes, since -infra will
be retiring in the future.  Additionally, we move into centos7 to
avoid the hurt of other projects using devstack-trusty.

Since we are installing puppet from gems, we don't need to rely on the
OS as much. However, if we want to add a devstack-trusty node in the
future, we now can easily.

Change-Id: I8d19231a5eccbfec7c0e035077aab47bf4ecc1b1
Signed-off-by: Paul Belanger <pabelanger@redhat.com>

[{'created': '2015-07-30 14:21:08.000000000', 'message': 'WSGI: use real service name in restart_keystone Exec

Before, when running the Exec which restart Keystone service, we used
$service_name but this is wrong because service_name can be keystone,
openstack-keystone or httpd.
On Ubuntu/Debian, Apache service name is not httpd but apache2.

So the service could never be restarted if we were 1/ running
Ubuntu/Debian 2/ changing the default domain name.

This patch looks up in puppetlabs-apache the real Apache service name
when $service_name is httpd (if WSGI is enabled and eventlet disabled).

That way, we are sure the service name that will be used will the right
one.
Also add some unit tests that validate this change.

Change-Id: I85226d862b63e227867ed43bc35d7fefc9e424cd
Closes-bug: #1479783
'}]
commit_message:
WSGI: use real service name in restart_keystone Exec

Before, when running the Exec which restart Keystone service, we used
$service_name but this is wrong because service_name can be keystone,
openstack-keystone or httpd.
On Ubuntu/Debian, Apache service name is not httpd but apache2.

So the service could never be restarted if we were 1/ running
Ubuntu/Debian 2/ changing the default domain name.

This patch looks up in puppetlabs-apache the real Apache service name
when $service_name is httpd (if WSGI is enabled and eventlet disabled).

That way, we are sure the service name that will be used will the right
one.
Also add some unit tests that validate this change.

Change-Id: I85226d862b63e227867ed43bc35d7fefc9e424cd
Closes-bug: #1479783

commit_message:
Enable Horizon to consume a Keystone v3 API endpoint

This patch enables Horizon to consume a Keystone v3 API endpoint.

This patch also introduces two variables to allow the endpoint to be
specified independently if required:
 - horizon_keystone_host: this defaults to the internal LB IP address
 - horizon_keystone_endpoint: this defaults to the internal Keystone
   endpoint

This patch also does the following:
 - properly consumes the horizon_ssl_no_verify role setting;
 - includes a little comment cleanup which does nothing but clutter
   the local_settings configuration file.

Closes-Bug: #1478996
Change-Id: I5b7ceeecab072ead6fd380dcef7a48f1978a56f2

commit_message:
tests: add an integration test

This change adds an integration test.

It need a devstack with heat/aodh/ceilometer/gnocchi setuped.

The test does the following:
* check no servers and alarms are present
* create a heat autoscaling stack with aodh alarms for gnocchi
* check that the stack creation succeed
* check the stack automatically grow according the alarm configuration
* check the gnocchi resource have been created
* delete the stack
* check everything have been deleted

This test use gabbi to talk with all API.

Change-Id: I897ef4aa359fa7b65c0f18b1999e403eb89045a7

commit_message:
Remove the compute inspector choice restriction

A recent change ( https://review.openstack.org/#/c/203319/ ) was pushed
into the compute inspector branch to identify the choices for the
varying Ceilometer inspectors.

The side effect of this change is that it limited the operator to only
be allowed to use those options.  Any other option would throw an error.

Given the approach to use plugins under the ceilometer.compute.virt
namespace, the inspectors can now reside out of tree.

It was discussed in the July 30th Ceilometer IRC meeting, and it was
decided instead that the current known options should instead be listed
in the help, rather than limiting via the choices attribute.  This
allows for plugins (ex. the PowerVM compute inspector) to be used.

Change-Id: Ie8f881b7b04372cab06d8c8b61693c5489b2b302

commit_message:
Update glance_store requirement to 0.7.1

This release has support for py34, so we can stop using glance_store
directly from git.

Change-Id: I60777b464da28fae4b27bb3d575a07091cea6b45
Depends-On: I4b3fe87fa11465d784f1158142c52e4f09001d27

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-07-06 04:14:49.000000000', 'message': "Improve the guestagent configuration manager

The current version of the configuration manager lacks
certain features that turn out to be required by some of the
ongoing projects.

 - The current implementation allows the caller to
   apply 'system' configuration overrides, but does not provide
   an easy way for removing them.
 - The current implementation of the RollingOverrideStrategy
   does not allow for an easy update of an existing configuration
   override via the guestagent API.
 - The manager duplicates some checks already made at a higher level
   (maximum number of configuration groups applied to an instance etc.)
   This duplication is not neccessary and more importantly may
   put the instance in a state difficult to recover from without
   direct access to the guestagent FS
   (e.g. configuration group gets detached in the Trove database, but
   not on the FS).

Proposed change:

 - Rework and simplify the override strategy implementation.
 - Remove the duplicate checks - the configuration manager leaves
   the validation on the API and does not impose any limits on the number
   of attached groups itself.
 - Allow the caller to remove 'system' overrides.
 - Replace the RollingOverrideStrategy with OneFileOverrideStrategy which
   uses the Import strategy to keep the overrides internally.
   When an override is applied or removed a new configuration file is
   generated by applying all changes on a saved-off base revision.
   This implementation based on the ImportOverrideStrategy allows
   great simplification of the code and provides an easy way to
   re-apply (edit) and remove existing overrides.

Change-Id: Icfd58deeaf6bb368912dffe69566034a65f5854e

commit_message:
Improve the guestagent configuration manager

The current version of the configuration manager lacks
certain features that turn out to be required by some of the
ongoing projects.

 - The current implementation allows the caller to
   apply 'system' configuration overrides, but does not provide
   an easy way for removing them.
 - The current implementation of the RollingOverrideStrategy
   does not allow for an easy update of an existing configuration
   override via the guestagent API.
 - The manager duplicates some checks already made at a higher level
   (maximum number of configuration groups applied to an instance etc.)
   This duplication is not neccessary and more importantly may
   put the instance in a state difficult to recover from without
   direct access to the guestagent FS
   (e.g. configuration group gets detached in the Trove database, but
   not on the FS).

Proposed change:

 - Rework and simplify the override strategy implementation.
 - Remove the duplicate checks - the configuration manager leaves
   the validation on the API and does not impose any limits on the number
   of attached groups itself.
 - Allow the caller to remove 'system' overrides.
 - Replace the RollingOverrideStrategy with OneFileOverrideStrategy which
   uses the Import strategy to keep the overrides internally.
   When an override is applied or removed a new configuration file is
   generated by applying all changes on a saved-off base revision.
   This implementation based on the ImportOverrideStrategy allows
   great simplification of the code and provides an easy way to
   re-apply (edit) and remove existing overrides.

Closes-Bug: 1471905
Change-Id: Icfd58deeaf6bb368912dffe69566034a65f5854e

commit_message:
storage: only retry connection, not driver finding

The current code will retry over and over to reload the driver from
stevedore if it fails to connect. That's not what we meant, we really
just want to retry the connection part.

Change-Id: I681029196f834999895a4d4186417c1da85a32ba

commit_message:
Stop using global conf object

This patch completely replaces the global conf object with a local one
built by aodh.service.prepare_service().

Change-Id: Ia5d37db7e3d5ddb858dd7ef30394bfb148109291

commit_message:
api: fix alarm group declaration

The aodh.opts list those options in the DEFAULT group but there are
actually registered in the alarm group. We deprecated the alarm group,
so let's move them and register them in DEFAULT as set in aodh.opts.

Change-Id: I01f192c1619790cb418cb23036349f5843372b27

commit_message:
Add std out to ssh exception.

Some commands in case of error redirect his output in stdout
instead of stderr. I suggest to combine stdout and stderr and pass
this string to ssh exception. It will help to understand better
errors in ssh tests.

Change-Id: Ied28043f0eaefa1c3a00b7e98e52b13a86873827

commit_message:
Added class SignalHandler

Singleton class Signal Handler is responsible for interacting
with signal module: allow to have several handlers assigned
to distinct signal. Added correct handling SIGINT signal.

Closes-Bug: #1477102

commit_message:
Keystone Federation Identity Provider Configuration

This change adds the bits necessary to configure Keystone as an
identity provider (IdP) for an external service provider (SP).

* New variables to configure Keystone as an identity provider are now
  supported under a root `keystone_idp` variable. Example configurations
  can be seen in Keystone's defaults file. This configuration includes
  the location of the signing certificate, authentication endpoints and
  list of allowed service providers.

* xmlsec1 is installed in the Keystone containers when IdP configuration
  is enabled.

* The IdP metadata and signing certiciate are generated and installed.

Implements: blueprint keystone-federation
Change-Id: I81455e593e3059633a55f7e341511d5ad9eba76f
(cherry picked from commit 18fcaaa7698f4336137ffd2ba28ca1072b1c44d3)

commit_message:
[gate] workaround to run tempest's setup.py

This patch is to run python setup with develop. However, there are some
issue from tempest dependency, we have to manually install those
dependency and run develop mode installation of tempest.

Change-Id: I69c13454e6e2b0e0be7a8e88e1ac897e46c55c48

commit_message:
Activate pep8 check that _ is imported

Remove the specification in tox.ini that _ is a builtin so that
it will no longer assume that _ does not need to be imported.
This helps ensure that the _ from i18n is used.

Activating this check did not flag any violations.

Change-Id: Ia8c7efe5bb30294c349b504d569e6ad7c602f246

commit_message:
Add missing slash if docker registry is specified

If user specifies registry a full image name is constructed by
concatenation of the registry, namespace and image. Currently
concatenation does not include '/' if registry is non-empty but
it should. If registry is empty '/' is not required.
This fix covers both use cases with help of Ansible filter.

Change-Id: I0588dd0da55d777e6caa7eb47d51b2435d38d5e0
Closes-Bug: #1479013

[{'created': '2015-07-29 21:41:43.000000000', 'message': "VPNaaS: Correcting method name for functional test

With the new DevStack plugin for neutron-vpnaas, the method names for
various stacking actions were renamed. One is used by the functional
test setup script tools/configure_for_vpn_func_testing.sh.

The change wasn't noticed, because the neutron-vpnaas repo still was
using DevStack's existing VPN setup, where the old method name is still
in use. But, when removing the VPN setup in DevStack, then the function
tests will fail.

This commit just renames the method to match the name of the DevStack
plugin method, instead of the older DevStack repo method. It'll be
needed, before upstreaming Iffa9901e24adbacb581425c4b38c7e8cff0da9e8.

Also, trying to use more of the plugin methods, when preparing ini
files.

Change-Id: Ib22a4b9abdc82c2b14d933b02329c6483c075ea8

commit_message:
VPNaaS: Correcting method name for functional test

With the new DevStack plugin for neutron-vpnaas, the method names for
various stacking actions were renamed. One is used by the functional
test setup script tools/configure_for_vpn_func_testing.sh.

The change wasn't noticed, because the neutron-vpnaas repo still was
using DevStack's existing VPN setup, where the old method name is still
in use. But, when removing the VPN setup in DevStack, then the function
tests will fail.

This commit renames the method to match the name of the DevStack
plugin method, instead of the older DevStack repo method. It'll be
needed, before upstreaming Iffa9901e24adbacb581425c4b38c7e8cff0da9e8.

In addition, it makes sure that VPN environment variables are available
for use by the configuration script, and reuses more plugin.sh code,
to remove duplication.

Change-Id: Ib22a4b9abdc82c2b14d933b02329c6483c075ea8

commit_message:
api: remove force_canonical option

This has been provided at the beginning but there is actually no chance
it ever has been used as we never provided a way for the user to tweak
the Pecan config itself. So let's get rid of it.

Change-Id: If410228b27d659c2e99aa8c51471bcdfb7c71e55

commit_message:
Remove "volume:services" rule from policy.json

The rule "volume:services": "rule:admin_api" does not seem to be used.
The cinder/api/contrib/services.py is using "volume_extension:services".
This change deletes "volume:services" rule from policy.json.

Change-Id: Id1d23e44c5b7e8361e21c8568ff67f0012e5c097
Closes-Bug: #1471990

commit_message:
Add decorator for translating function

Use decorator to check raw data before retranslating.
If raw data is same with cached self.raw_state,
don't translate data, return empty list directly.

Change-Id: Ibc25a032adfb0323d7eb36f22b8b3b5dbc2a7f12
Partial-Bug: #1473924

subject: Fix unittests
messages:
[{'account_id': 16173, 'date': '2015-07-27 09:05:03.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 10068, 'date': '2015-07-27 09:05:09.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

commit_message:
Add pluggable metrics backend for Ironic and IPA

This blueprint proposes the addition of metric data reporting features
to Ironic, and Ironic Python Agent (IPA). Initially, this will include a
statsd reference implementation, but will be sufficiently generic to
permit the creation of alternative backends.

Blueprint: add-pluggable-metrics-backend-for-ironic-and-ipa

Change-Id: Ie5d7a83780252259c099ed6e2dfd6e4cd7fe453b

commit_message:
Switch to the oslo_log library

Remove the log module of oslo-incubator.
Move the WritableLogger wrapper to the base_wsgi module.
Add oslo.log to the requirements.

commit_message:
Update dhcp agent cache for network:dhcp ports

When a network with a dhcp_enabled subnet is scheduled on a dhcp
agent, dhcp driver creates the network:dhcp port for the subnet.
However, the port info is not updated in dhcp agents internal cache.
Subsequently if the user deletes the network:dhcp port, the port is
properly deleted on the server side (i.e., in the database) and when
the port_delete_end notification is sent to the dhcp agent, it simply
ignores it as the port entry would be missing in the cache. This patch
fixes this issue by updating the dhcp agents cache when dhcp driver
creates the network:dhcp port for the subnets.

Closes-Bug: #1478426
Change-Id: I69f5834dd964a4320c606c4e0aa2cdba70416943

commit_message:
Configure only cluster or API in devstack plugin

Following the changes made in devmido in which it now starts only one
of midonet API or cluster API, adjust the devstack plugin script to
only configure one of them.

Partially Implements: blueprint clean-up-devstack-plugin
Sign-off-by: Ryu Ishimoto <ryu@midokura.com>

Change-Id: I90e837fc862d020f64c32d96c329eac19a8d8fe4

Franois, your comment was "I prefer to keep I18n" and that's exactly what this patch does now. Could you clarify your -1, please?'}, {'account_id': 8557, 'date': '2015-07-27 12:38:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

I am not agree to change the name like this without a common decision from the team. This change has been discussed and decided.

If we decide to change, Translation is not the best choice because it is only a task of a Localization or Internationalization process. So it is too restrictive regarding to works done by the team.

The discussion should be more about Internalization (I18N) or Localization (L10n).

More informations : https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internationalization_and_localization

In any case it has to be a team choice, which is not the case of the related changes .'}, {'account_id': 6547, 'date': '2015-07-27 12:40:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I'm confused: This is a change *to* i18n, so dropping translation. But you seem to argue that translation is wrong - so the change does the right thing.

I agree that team consensus should be reached for such a rename - and will only +2 this when Daisy gave her +1 as PTL."}, {'account_id': 8557, 'date': '2015-07-27 12:48:24.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1

Hy Andras, 

My mistake and all my apologizes I didn't read the patch in the right way, I saw #openstack-i18n to #openstack-translation, probably because we already had this conversation. 

No pb for the change but it will have to be globally communicated because the #openstack-translation is already know as the place where you can find translators.

Sorry again :("}, {'account_id': 819, 'date': '2015-07-27 12:54:14.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Concerning consensus: I emailed the mailing-list one month ago (http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-i18n/2015-June/001179.html) and mentioned it a couple times in the IRC channel since, and didn't get any complaint, so assumed lazy consensus :) Of course I'd like a formal approval from Daisy.

For the transition, we should setup a forward as per https://wiki.ubuntu.com/IRC/MovingChannels#Forwarding, which would make the impact minimal."}, {'account_id': 9162, 'date': '2015-07-27 23:08:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 6609, 'date': '2015-07-28 06:38:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 3108, 'date': '2015-07-28 07:08:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1

Agree to change to be consensus.
But we have been in #openstack-translation for a long time.
#openstack-translation is well known for translators.
I prefer to keep both of them for quite a while till more translators would know about the new channel.'}, {'account_id': 819, 'date': '2015-07-28 08:29:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Hi Daisy,

commit_message:
Refactor plugin name checking logic

This patch reworks the plugin name checking so that it can be shared
among different plugin types. Major revisions include:

- Add a new exception type 'InvalidPlugin' for plugin related
  exceptions.
- Remove the 'ProfileValidationFailure' exception type, which is not
  useful and it is confusing. Replace it with 'InvalidPlugin'.
- Remove the 'InvalidPolicyType' exception type, which is not very
  useful. Replace it with 'InvalidPlugin'.
- Combine profile name checking and policy name checking into a shared
  function. Revised the test case as needed.

Change-Id: Ia02eb1e4fa84c314b04aa656277aed46965c5c9b

commit_message:
Make HTTPAccepted exception response in JSON format

HTTPAccepted should not be considered as an exception,
and it is returned to the client as TEXT type, but SDK
wants it to be a JSON, this patch fixes it.

Change-Id: I134df15138583d0fd7070b95c5b8a3eceb56c8d2

commit_message:
Remove cpu_sink as it does not pertain to powervm

The cpu_sink as defined in the default pipeline.yaml does not apply to
PowerVM.  This is because the PowerVM compute inspector has a CPU
Utilization inspector built in.

This change provides an updated default pipeline.yaml that is applicable
for operators wishing to make use of the powervm compute inspector.

This change also removes the network sink as that was also an issue as
network metrics came back.

Change-Id: I4e7cae715fc77c5e399bd3c6d33afdc8fa02d890
Closes-Bug: 1475362

commit_message:
libvirt:Add a driver API to inject an NMI

This patch adds a new driver API to inject an NMI to an instance.
This API is implemented by libvirt driver.

NMI (Non-maskable Interruption) is used to trigger a special function such as
the kernel crash dump mechanism.

DocImpact

Change-Id: Iaf63352139c466430d3304a87a66398133541fac
Implements: blueprint inject-nmi

commit_message:
Fix typo in Operations Guide

Fixes a typo: /etc/fuel-creamirror/common.cfg
--> /etc/fuel-createmirror/common.cfg
in Setting up local mirrors section of the
Operations Guide.

Change-Id: I4cf34f2c7a8f4facbf797632cdb0dcd560b2dcf9
Closes-Bug: #1477238

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-06-23 23:28:58.000000000', 'message': "Add plural names for quota resources

Introduce a 'plural_name' attribute in the BaseResource
class in the neutron.quota.resource module. This will
enable to specify the plural name of a resource when it's

commit_message:
Add plural names for quota resources

Introduce a 'plural_name' attribute in the BaseResource
class in the neutron.quota.resource module. This will
enable to specify the plural name of a resource when it's
entered in the quota registry.

This will come handy for managing reservations and also
removes the need for passing the collection name when
counting a resource.

Also, the name of the 'resources' parameter for the
_count_resource routine has ben changed to collection_name,
as the previous one was misleading, since it led to believe
it should be used for a collection, whereas it is simply
the name of a collection.

Change-Id: I0b61ba1856e9552cc14574be28fec6c77fb8783c
Related-Blueprint: better-quotas

Undo tox -e docs pip install sphinx workaround

Now that we require at least pbr 1.3 and that has
commit 61a3a1ecdf99c680e509742fdc6c441b499af130 in it,
let's remove the workaround.

Change-Id: I4074b05a823d32f5db0051062527b0db4d379b62
Related-Bug: #1473401

commit_message:
Removed support of Hive 0.12 and Impala 1.2.3 from MapR plugin

Hive 0.12 was removed from MapR ecosystem repo so now it's
not supported in plugin. Support of Impala 1.2.3 was removed
because it depends on Hive 0.12 which is unavailable now.

Change-Id: Ice4b735a69df5af61f15c999e03a35046f3ca9b3
Closes-Bug: #1477084

commit_message:
Make OAuth testcase use actual request headers

OAuth test verifies that access_token manager's methods make requests with
certain parameters. It is supposed to use values from mocked http handler
and compare them with referential values acquired from oauth client.

But instead of using values from mocked handler, it used the values from
oauth client and compared them with values from the client acquired using
attributes, basically testing oauthlib and not access_token manager's
methods.

Make the test compare correct values and remove check of timestamp,
which was useless because it is always mocked in tests and not provided in
actual requests.

As a consequence, use of get_oauth_params, which changed in oauthlib
1.0 and blocked the gate, was removed.

Closes-Bug: 1477177
Closes-Bug: 1477247
Change-Id: I5e049163f84fde5827104fd4a6441222eb08468f

commit_message:
Refresh instance info cache within lock

Fix interface attachment bug where multiple concurrent attachment
requests can cause corruption of the nova instance info cache. This
change refreshes the info cache object from the database whilst
holding the refresh-cache lock, ensuring that changes are
synchronised.

Change-Id: I6ea2eda8a61f418b0c32f13a7ed6904352712857
Closes-Bug: #1467581

  If 'keystone_v3_domains' function will be run earlier than
  'heat_handle_requests', auth url will be changed from v2.0 to v3.
  Then all next requests will be with v3 auth url.
  To protect users from such mistake we need to change API to v2.0 back.

Change-Id: I87c2e1bfd8de9204aa5cfcf9718c0396c6650646
"}]
commit_message:
Be sure that v2 API (not v3) is used in heat_handle_requests function

  If 'keystone_v3_domains' function will be run earlier than
  'heat_handle_requests', auth url will be changed from v2.0 to v3.
  Then all next requests will be with v3 auth url.
  To protect users from such mistake we need to change API to v2.0 back.

Change-Id: I87c2e1bfd8de9204aa5cfcf9718c0396c6650646

commit_message:
Add retries for heat domain commands

  Implement retries for:
    * heat domain creation
    * get_domain_id heat function
  These retries could be useful in some cases:
    * heat engine, heat api or keystone services
      haven't actually started yet
      (service initialization is in progress)
    * there are some connectivity issues to keystone

Change-Id: If89a595c909f277febaa1e33acc409567d281647

commit_message:
Use form field errors on volume Extend form

Now when extending a volume to a new size which is less then the current
one, we will pop up an error warning message on the top of the form instead
of beside the new size field. now change to use field specified error class
for more accurate.

Closes-Bug: #1480001
Change-Id: I2ee1a562bf548e78d657a3c5bd3307eacf6a3ab1

Answers to Ryan's questions

1. are we sure that resources counts will provide enough triggers to ensure a count isn't out of sync for appreciable amounts of time?

With the logic being implemented here it actually does not matter how long a resource tracker is out of sync. Indeed when a count is performed if the tracker is out of sync it is immediately synchronized.

It is true that a periodic resynchronisation might probably constitute an improvement, but a similar periodic task in Nova turned out to be more of a hindrance than a help. therefore I implemented resource tracking in this way at the moment. the triggers employed here, as stated in the devref are not the final solution. I don't want to rely on sqlalchemy events forever (also because one has to be careful to use declarative model classes). However, we really needed an intermediate layer between the API and the plugin to install the hooks necessary for resource tracking, and Neutron lacks that at the moment.

2. Is there a possibility that resyncing on resource counts will cause us headaches when clustering?

If by clustering you mean an active/active database cluster, resync should not cause any headache as it's not acquiring any lock or performing any operation which might result problematic in active/active db clusters.

If you mean multiple neutron servers, there should be no headaches. One negative aspect could be that the resync operation is needlessy performed multiple times - in case of concurrent reads performed by multiple workers, but I guess that this is something that can be optimized in the future
One thing that has been puzzling me for a while is the possibility that concurrency might result in incorrect operations. Assume 3 workers: W1, W2, and W3. W1 reads data, which are dirty at time t1. W2 inserts data at time t2 > t1, and W3 reads again data at time t3 > t2, finding the tracker dirty again because of the insert.
Then W3 writes at time t4 > t3 the update counter, and W1 does the same at time t5 > t4, but unfortunately overwrites the correct counter with an obsolete one. I have a suspect this could be a real possibility, albeit remote. I think some timestapping can help the situation. I am not yet sure if I should use absolute timestamps or something like vector clocks, but I am sure that this is something I'll take care of once these patches are merged, because the way resources are counted today is completely unreliable."}, {'account_id': 11682, 'date': '2015-07-09 13:20:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 12: Code-Review+1

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-06-05 18:12:26.000000000', 'message': 'Introduce usage data tracking for Neutron

This patch introduces application logic support for tracking
Neutron resource usage data, thus introducing a different
way of enforcing quota limits, which now relies on records
tracking resource usage for each tenant.

When these records go "out-of-sync" with actual resource usage,
the quota usage table entry is marked "dirty".
And it will be resynchronized the next time a resource count is
requested. Changes in resource utilization are detected using
SQLAlchemy events.

This patch however does not automatically enable resource usage
tracking for any plugin. Plugins must explicitly declare for which
resources they wish to enable tracking. To this aim, this patch
provides the @tracked_resources decorator.

As some operators might wish to not use resource usage tracking, this
patch adds the track_quota_usage configuration option. If set to
False, DB-level usage tracking will not be performed, and
resources will be counted as before, ie: invoking a plugin method.

Usage tracking is performed using a new resource type,
TrackedResource, which can work side by side with CountableResource,
the one Neutron used so far. To this aim a ResourceRegistry class
has been introduced for registering and managing resources. Most
of the resource management code previously embedded in the
QuotaEngine class is being moved to ResourceRegistry as a part of
this patch.

Partially implements blueprint better-quota

commit_message:
Introduce usage data tracking for Neutron

This patch introduces application logic support for tracking
Neutron resource usage data, thus introducing a different
way of enforcing quota limits, which now relies on records
tracking resource usage for each tenant.

When these records go "out-of-sync" with actual resource usage,
the quota usage table entry is marked "dirty".
And it will be resynchronized the next time a resource count is
requested. Changes in resource utilization are detected using
SQLAlchemy events.

This patch however does not automatically enable resource usage
tracking for any plugin. Plugins must explicitly declare for which
resources they wish to enable tracking. To this aim, this patch
provides the @tracked_resources decorator.

As some operators might wish to not use resource usage tracking, this
patch adds the track_quota_usage configuration option. If set to
False, DB-level usage tracking will not be performed, and
resources will be counted as before, ie: invoking a plugin method.

Usage tracking is performed using a new resource type,
TrackedResource, which can work side by side with CountableResource,
the one Neutron used so far. To this aim a ResourceRegistry class
has been introduced for registering and managing resources. Most
of the resource management code previously embedded in the
QuotaEngine class is being moved to ResourceRegistry as a part of
this patch.

Partially implements blueprint better-quota

Change-Id: If461399900973a38d7b82e0b3ac54fc052f09529

Adds python-magnumclient>=0.2.1

It adds magnumnclient into global requirements as its already
used in other project such as Heat.
project.txt already has entry for python-magnumclient.

commit_message:
Add more info level log to deploy_utils.work_on_disk() method

The deploy_utils.work_on_disk() is an important method for pxe_*
drivers, so add more info log for debugging helps identify if
breaks in the work_on_disk_method call.

Change-Id: I6ab7b4ca38161dce9afc9cbab8e19a721c301466
Closes-Bug: #1410098

commit_message:
Refactoring for HTTP client

This patch performs a small refactoring of the HTTP client
in order to resolve technical dept and fix a few bugs:

 - Removes exit() calls from HTTP client so it
   can be used as a library.
 - Adds options for configuring http proxy and http timeout
 - Uses requests.Session in order to have a common configuration
   for all requests and utilize connection pooling
 - Uses Keystone service discovery to get Fuel's and OSTF's endpoints

DocImpact
Closes-bug: #1454343
Closes-bug: #1459964

Nova client requires providing backup_type, this backup_type is only a tag
which used for filtering images, so it could be any user-defined tag.

commit_message:
Correct backup_type param description

Nova client requires providing backup_type, this backup_type is only a tag
which used for filtering images, so it could be any user-defined tag.

This patch corrects param description in _rotate_backups to avoid misleading of
restricting 'daily'/'weekly'.

Related-Bug: #1298157
Change-Id: I1f73e753524231cd89b37fe06bd9e3934371a986

commit_message:
Remove key-pair-details.html duplicate

In the new launch instance wizard, there appears to be an extra
key-pair-details.html under the security groups step. It is not used.

Remove:
launch-instance/security-groups/keypair-details.html

Keep:
launch-instance/keypair/keypair-details.html

Change-Id: Iee13034ab1d0f891189ed84dd1a366705b5d13b2
Closes-Bug: #1479998

commit_message:
Update alarm history only if change in alarm property

When alarm's property is updated with the same
value, an empty record is added to the alarm
history output.

This fix omits the update to alarm history if
there no changes to any alarm property.

Change-Id: Ib860f371979896c7eedd41a25c3b640bb6dbee31
Closes-Bug: 1465550
(cherry picked from commit e5b3988c7cb01d2230f67c41aa76935a11b0e42a)

commit_message:
Fix WSGI replacement_start_response() on Python 3

Replace a/b with a//b to get an integer division.

Add more tests to Python 3.4 in tox.ini.

Change-Id: Ibd259874b211c80d3d8d3b328a105fc742b2c583

commit_message:
Virtual IP reservation check

Test for covering 2 VIPs reservation:
- create and install vip_reservation plugin
with predefined metadata.yaml and network_roles.yaml
- check that 2 VIPs are present in database and astute.yaml

Change-Id: I5f72cd231941301c97a9079ef631e8169a55aace
Implements: blueprint virtual-ip-reservation-check

commit_message:
Reuse stuff from OSLO's RequestContext

RequestContext in OSLO was updated a long time ago and now
contains some of the extra information Ironic's RequestContext
had to store by its own.

This patch re-uses existing properties of the OSLO's RequestContext
making them more compatible.

Change-Id: Ie2365dcfa99df41233cdce96aa487d99a67cba13

commit_message:
Allow using custom help and complete commands

By default the App class overrides both help and complete
commands even if their custom implementations were specified
as appropriate entry points.

This patch allows having custom help and complete commands w/o
overriding methods of the App class.

Change-Id: I4c29f08c5d252f85e3ed683a1501097b64c1facc

Raise BadRequest for invalid replication status

Raise HTTPBadRequest instead of HTTPNotFound while creating
a volume from an existing source replica with invalid replication
status 'disabled'.

APIImpact

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC

api: fix alarm deletion and update

The API allow the actions to be null.

This allow the alarm to be deleted and updated in this case.

Closes bug: #1479274

commit_message:
Add devstackgaterc to manage gate tests

In order to be able to manage the tests to run at the gate, add
devstackgaterc with the regex indicating the tests to run.

The regex generated runs the same set of tests as those running at the
gate currently, which are:

 * network API tests
 * scenario tests

blueprint midonet-devstackgaterc

Change-Id: Icb7402fffaf6523051a36c98d121007a223586c9

[{'created': '2015-03-03 15:49:56.000000000', 'message': 'WIP: Sample keystone client usage for k2k federation

In order to run this code you'll need this recent keystone patch
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/159865/

and in-progress keystone client patch
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/159022/
including modifying the last line to return resp.content as noted
in the review

In order to make the calls I'm using for K2K federation clearer I've
written this sample code which includes the set of calls I'd expect to
make in a k2k federated environment to get a scoped token from the idp
keystone, exchange it for a saml assertion, present the saml assertion
to the sp (remote) keystone to get an unscoped token and list the
projects.

I'm linking output and keystone log info for 2 different scenarios
1) running the code as is, with the potentially uneeded call at
line 94 included:
http://pastebin.com/DEs0nK43

2) running the code with line 94 commented out:
http://pastebin.com/YUkMjAU1

In either case, this sample relies on code that shows a current
shortcoming in the keystone client for k2k federation: there is no
way to obtain an unscoped token from a keystone sp based either
directly on the saml assertion, or based on providing the scoped
token from the keystone idp.  I'd expect one of these two methods
to be provided through some sort of authorization plugin.

Note that my "real" patch https://review.openstack.org/#/c/159910/
is able to obtain the list of projects on the remote/sp keystone by
making yet another call to k2k.py.  This makes me think that either
keystone client can't handle k2k yet or I'm using the client wrong.
In either case, I'd like feedback!

Change-Id: I8e99ff668832bee87fb4598835c4f420e5fe275c

This patch demonstrates the calls needed to obtain an initial
keystone token, then get tokens from the defined remote/
SP keystones.

In order to run you'll need in-progress python-keystoneclient
patch https://review.openstack.org/#/c/199347/

commit_message:
Lower log level of errors caused by user requests to INFO

When webob exception is returned, error level log is
always recorded even though we return 4xx (client error)
to users. 4xx error in response code means errors due to
user requests, so error level log is not appropriate.
This commit lowers the log level to INFO for such events.

Currently only case I see is webob.exc.HTTPNotFound returned
by the policy engine when a user requests an operation
prohibited by the policy, but I think there is no reason
we deal with 404 specially in neutron.api.v2.resource.

Closes-Bug: #1473556
(cherry picked from commit 2d390876b99c7ee227543663aa7345ba4bef714c)

Conflicts:
	neutron/api/v2/resource.py

Change-Id: I9f042a90c9bf528be7cb835d7fe818ed1879054b

commit_message:
devstack/settings: Stop tweaking the list of enabled services

Because it's a user's responsibility to decide the set of services
to run.  I.e. it belongs to local.conf.

NOTE: This commit fixes CIs.  Currently, while q-lbaas is not
enabled in project-config, it's (accidentially afaik) enabled here,
without configuring an appropriate service provider.

Change-Id: I1e97070256950ba6c2e240bb6903213a08b3d5a9

commit_message:
Update package cache before installing packages

On Debian/Ubuntu, update the package cache so we do not
try to download old and out of date packages when creating
test virtual machines.

Change-Id: Ica0879b7b6c3bdbf7a520a6e746b5d1cc670fe61
Closes-Bug: #1480046

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-07-31 13:03:36.000000000', 'message': "Add 'create_plan_only' flag for reporter script

In order to create test plans for Fuel images right after
a new iso is assembled, added new flag '-c' / '--create-plan-only'
which disables uploading tests results, so script doesn't require
jobs with tests. Example of usage:

python fuelweb_test/testrail/report.py -v -j 7.0.all -N 112 -c

Closes-bug: #1480215
Change-Id: I73b7e5b30ca1e230b6406874e801d04f481e4abb
"}]
commit_message:
Add 'create_plan_only' flag for reporter script

In order to create test plans for Fuel images right after
a new iso is assembled, added new flag '-c' / '--create-plan-only'
which disables uploading tests results, so script doesn't require
jobs with tests. Example of usage:

python fuelweb_test/testrail/report.py -v -j 7.0.all -N 112 -c

Closes-bug: #1480215
Change-Id: I73b7e5b30ca1e230b6406874e801d04f481e4abb

commit_message:
Add puppet-murano to Puppet Modules Project

This change adds puppet-murano to the OpenStack Puppet
Modules project, which will contain the module necessary to configure
and manage Murano with Puppet.

Change-Id: Id846941c9002194e76a6ac31c1979d410aa25fb9
Depends-On: Ia7e917b3032ef5ea56b33cf92e6b7c2d62674f6a

commit_message:
storage: always use get_connection_from_config()

There's no way to connect to a backend only using an URL, because of
parameters such as mongodb_replicaset, etc. So we just remove
get_connection(url) function and always relies on
get_connection_from_config(conf).

Change-Id: I39fabbc78325709150dc7f4edb474c7bd9501205

commit_message:
Always take into account config file values

Some methods were declared with the default parameters specified as
CONF.<foo> values. Those values will be evaluated only once during
module build time. So, the values speficied in config file won't be
passed into those methods as config file values will be available
only after config file gets parsed in run-time.

Change-Id: Ic8e24be4fdc0ce165d8142d47405373acaf4a803
Closes-Bug: #1479307

commit_message:
Use 'internalURL' as endpoint for nova-api in vcenter_hooks.py

Keystone returns by default 'publicURL' to client which might be
protected by SSL/TLS security.  This may lead to SSLErrors since we are
dealing with self signed certificates.  Instead of using 'publicURL'
switch to 'internalURL'

While here change '#!/usr/bin/python' to '#!/usr/bin/env python',
should be no functional change.

Change-Id: I2e47ba3e8f62cbfafc77a2945fb9c0b39388689f
Closes-bug: #1479774

commit_message:
nailgun::astute: set the bootstrap profile in astuted.conf

In MOS 7.0 several bootstrap images and corresponding cobbler profiles
can exist. Astute needs to know which bootstrap profile should be used
to correctly reboot the nodes being (re-)provisioned.

Closes-Bug: #1479882
Depends-On: I844e30311938fcd2c0aea6f558862205ba2a9982

Change-Id: I3ca4c0a172f1b607048523a7c0cc70aa76a83ee1

'}, {'created': '2015-07-21 10:50:15.000000000', 'message': 'gnocchi: concurrently post resource/measures

Without the batch dispatch, oslo.messaging calls 64 (rpc_thread_pool_size)
times record_metering_data, each message contains ~ 1 sample,
64 concurrently HTTP requests are done to gnocchi with 1 sample each.

But with the batch, this 64 record_metering_data are merged into one
record_metering_data call of the gnocchi dispatch with 64 samples
into the payload (more if the rpc_thread_pool_size and the batch
size are increased).

This change allows in this case to parallize the handling of this
samples by creating a threadpool. Each task done in the
thread corresponds to the job to for one resource.

commit_message:
gnocchi: concurrently post resource/measures

Without the batch dispatch, oslo.messaging calls 64 (rpc_thread_pool_size)
times record_metering_data, each message contains ~ 1 sample,
64 concurrently HTTP requests are done to gnocchi with 1 sample each.

But with the batch, this 64 record_metering_data are merged into one
record_metering_data call of the gnocchi dispatch with 64 samples
into the payload (more if the rpc_thread_pool_size and the batch
size are increased).

This change allows in this case to parallize the handling of this
samples by creating a threadpool. Each task done in the
thread corresponds to the job to for one resource.

Change-Id: I4df91cfc086b6740ed35afe25acd48eac999dda3

commit_message:
Adds batch dispatcher

This adds a batch dispatcher.

It waits for N seconds (life) or for N messages (size) in the
samples/events queue. And then do one call to others dispatchers
with all samples/events merged.

Example of configuration use this dispatcher:

  [DEFAULT]
  rpc_thread_pool_size = 512
  dispatcher = batch

  [dispatcher_batch]
  size = 512
  dispatcher = gnocchi

oslo.messaging threads are hold until the samples/events is
really dispatched to:

* propagate exception correctly to the initial oslo.messaging thread.
* requeue/ack messages correctly.
* unack messages if collector crash or (unexpectedly) stopped.

Change-Id: I4f53051faebdf96888f1b1de8f351d525781e819
