yeah this is ok

but the current situation with pep8 and the E12X rules is sort of annoying:

https://github.com/PyCQA/pep8/issues/256

Also, as with every pep8 change - I'll have to fix some bugs in my vim plugins, but that's fine.

I'm not sure if after the pep8 issues get worked out if we can get the new pep8 version until we also upgrade hacking?  Luckily other OpenStack people seem to care about this way more than I do - so it's quite likely if just ignore it, at some point in the future someone will show up with a "bump to hacking 0.11" change and we'll have a whole new set of bugs!

If the E12X rules really start to annoy people I'd be open to adding some of them to the blacklist given the current state of things.'}, {'account_id': 9107, 'date': '2015-07-30 09:56:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

(3 comments)

> but the current situation with pep8 and the E12X rules is sort of annoying:

Well, this can be fixed later. I prefer to first upgrade hacking 0.10, and then discuss each check. As I wrote in comments, I tried to not ignore existing E checks, as asked by Alister.

> I'm not sure if after the pep8 issues get worked out if we can get the new pep8 version until we also upgrade hacking?

The current practice in OpenStack is to only rely on hacking which pins versions of pep8 and flake8.

Technically, I think that it's possible to upgrade pep8 if you put a "pep8>=..." after hacking in test-requirements.txt. Hum wait, the requested pep8 vrsion should be in global requirements. I'm not sure that it will work (you have to collaborate with other projects for that.)

>  (...) at some point in the future someone will show up with a "bump to hacking 0.11" change and we'll have a whole new set of bugs!

What do you mean by "bugs"? You mean that bumping hacking can make "tox -e pep8" to fail?

We will see when hacking 0.11 will be released. We are still free to ignore new checks when hacking is upgraded, or even ignore old checks which became more strict.

> If the E12X rules really start to annoy people I'd be open to adding some of them to the blacklist given the current state of things.

I don't know error codes, so I have no opinion on the specific case of E12x. In general I think that the code becomes more readable with my patches to fix pep8 warnings (even if I didn't write these patches for that, but only to "fix" tox -e pep8). When I compare old and new code, I prefer the new code.

Writing patches to conform to new stricter pep8 rules is annoying. But when you write new code which respects these rules, it should be less annoying, no?

It's like having to fix all bytes vs unicode issues at once when you port existing python 2 code to python 3. In my experience, writing new code which directly handles correctly bytes and unicode is much easier, than porting existing code.'}, {'account_id': 7847, 'date': '2015-07-30 10:08:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

(1 comment)

just one comment'}, {'account_id': 7847, 'date': '2015-07-30 10:12:22.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1

i don't think that comment indent is a blocker"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-07-30 10:12:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Starting gate jobs.
http://status.openstack.org/zuul/'}, {'account_id': 1179, 'date': '2015-07-30 17:26:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Workflow+1

I'm not sure why I feel compelled to explain myself... I think this is for
 other maintainers that review the rest of the patches in this patch chain, or
 come back to look at it after the fact when they get confused why good code
 doesn't lint.  Victor, you really should feel free to ignore me - you've got
 my +2 - I wanted this change to merge and eventually zuul will make it so!
 
 > > but the current situation with pep8 and the E12X rules is sort of annoying:
 > Well, this can be fixed later.
 
 Can it?  the pep8 version being pinned by hacking currently won't pass the
 examples in the pep8 document?  The authors solution in pep8 1.6 was to ignore
 the check as "unenforceable" - pretty annoying.
 
 > Hum wait, the requested pep8 vrsion should be in global requirements. I'm not
 > sure that it will work (you have to collaborate with other projects for that.)
 
 Ok, so it can't be "fixed later" - unless OpenStack decides to deal with it -
 my guess is someone will care and deal with it tho - my strong preference is
 to just ignore it and work on more important things than linting code that's
 already quite maintainable using the tools we have currently.  But I'm trying
 to be supportive of other actors with different priorties that might help them
 and don't hurt me too much.
 
 > > (...) at some point in the future someone will show up with a "bump to
 > > hacking 0.11" change and we'll have a whole new set of bugs!
 
 > What do you mean by "bugs"?
 
 I mean new checks in pep8 that fail on code that's fine.  Just because a check
 fails doesn't mean the code is more maintainable if it passes the check - and
 it isn't always about if check should be ignored - sometimes it's just the
 code that is trying to enfoce the style guide has a bug.  Do you understand
 that even if the pep8 *tool* fails a line of code it doesn't mean the code
 does not conform to pep8 if the pep8 tool has a bug?  The goal is not to make
 the code pass the linter - the goal is more maintainable code.  And it's the
 *code* I want to maintain - not the ecosystem of tools trying to help me make
 the code more maintainable.  It's all far to meta for me.
 
 > In general I think that the code becomes more readable with my patches to fix
 > pep8 warnings
 
 Well, yes, except, there's a bug in pep8 1.5 (which was worked around in pep8
 1.6) to make it so that the examples given in pep8 pass the pep8 tool's
 checks.  In general I find any code that passes pep8 readable enough, and
 althought slightly annoyed that code which conforms to the pep8 style guide
 will not lint in swift after this change - I will live.
 
 Overtime, I'll fix my editor so that's it's more work to write code that
 doesn't lint than does.   Hopefully everyone else has similarly hackable
 tools.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-07-31 01:01:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

commit_message:
Fix pep8 E warning for hacking 0.10

Fix pep8 warnings of the E category of hacking 0.10:

* E113: unexpected indentation
* E121: continuation line under-indented for hanging indent
* E122: continuation line missing indentation or outdented
* E123: closing bracket does not match indentation of opening bracket's
  line
* E126: continuation line over-indented for hanging indent
* E251: unexpected spaces around keyword / parameter equals

Change-Id: I0b24eebdf1a37dc1b572b6c9a3d3d4832d050237

commit_message:
System class was forgotten in core library manifest

MistralClient class stub was not present in io.murano
manifest and thus not used. This caused extra API call
on each deployment

Closes-Bug: #1480184
Change-Id: Ie9628104982995ab70df24cf5d7a57be6429e256

commit_message:
favicon, logo and logo-splash should allow theme overrides

favicon, logo and logo-splash are all elements that should
be easy to customize within a theme.  By adding this path
to the STATICFILES_DIR, this enables very granular overrides
of any of the images located within dashboard/img, by simply
adding an 'img' directory to your custom theme directory (or
static directory) and providing an image with the same file
name.

Closes-Bug: #1448283
Change-Id: I4feb229cac805e1b1fa3a55b5ecea1339a9fc8f9
Co-Authored-By: Tracy Jones <tjones@vmware.com>
Co-Authored-By: Diana Whitten <hurgleburgler@gmail.com>

commit_message:
documentation on integration test procedures

This documents thow to install and configure the various
elements to setup an integration test environment:

  * freezer installation
  * api configuration
  * scheduler usage

Change-Id: I8fb9919e3345f3b63347c238d9173c3535808ebe
Implements: blueprint integration-tests-doc

commit_message:
Add trystack-site to infra

We recently approved an infra-spec to host trystack.o.o[1]; as such we
need to import the current trystack.org website bits into infra.

NOTE: this request does not affect how or where the sandbox
environments runs. This is outside the scope of this repo.

[1] http://specs.openstack.org/openstack-infra/infra-specs/specs/trystack-site.html

Change-Id: I1651f35353705ba8c869bf245dbfc6bbb9588e27
Signed-off-by: Paul Belanger <pabelanger@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Adds proper isolation to templated catalog tests

Previously the templated catalog implementation wasn't really being
tested properly. The read/write tests, while passing, tested the KVS
implementation that will soon be removed.

A bad side effect of using KVS as a base is that the read operations
don't use the data from the template. They use only the data that
was modified by crud. This is why we didn't realize that the read
operations were incorrect.

Change-Id: I91ec863eabbf6074590e7f2ca43307b8b5133cf4

commit_message:
Add unit tests for create/update/delete_agent

We have a plan to migrate service clients to tempest-lib from Tempest.
However, we are not doing enough tests for service clients now.
This patch adds unit tests for the methods create_agent, update_agent
and delete_agent.
In addition, this patch changes update_agent method because we will
stop truncating the top key and this change will be helpful for doing
that. Aslo this patch removes bytes casts because encode('utf-8')
returns bytes data, so current bytes calls are redundant.

Change-Id: I85cf43007c0654bb7747ff3518a19894b34271f8

commit_message:
Remove deprecated SimpleScheduler

This has been deprecated for three releases now. It's time! By default
it was already having Cinder use the FilterScheduler with certain
weighers and filters to continue the chance behavior, so definitely not
scary!

Closes-Bug: #1478446
UpgradeImpact: Deprecated SimpleScheduler removed
Change-Id: I10f63bb189b7c894dcc6dccc857cf22698cc5f95

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-07-03 16:29:56.000000000', 'message': "Refactor diskfile

This patch mostly eliminates the duplicate code that was
deliberately left in place during EC review to avoid major
churn of the diskfile module prior to the kilo release.

This focuses on obvious de-duplication and shuffling code
between classes. It deliberately does not attempt to
hammer out every last piece of de-duplication where that
would introduce more complex changes - that can come later.

Code is moved from the module level and from ECDiskFile*
classes into new BaseDiskFile* classes.

Concrete classes for replication and EC policy retain their
existing names i.e. DiskFile[Manager|Writer|Reader|] and
ECDiskFile[Manager|Writer|Reader|] respectively.

Knock-on changes:

- fix bug whereby get_hashes was ignoring self.reclaim_age
  and always using the default arg value.

- replication diskfile manager now deletes a tombstone that is older
  than reclaim_age even when there is a newer .meta file.

- replication diskfile manager will no longer raise an
  AssertionError if only a .meta file is found during
  hash_cleanup_listdir.

- fix stale test in test_auditor.py: test_with_tombstone didn't
  make much sense other than to verify that a tombstone is not
  removed by auditor, but the test setup was convoluted and I think
  dates back to when object puts did not clean up the object dir.
  Now that they do you have to try harder to create a dir with
  a tombstone and a data file.

TODO: the naming of _get_hashes() and get_hashes() needs to be
fixed:
  - both are called from other modules so neither should have

commit_message:
Refactor diskfile

This patch mostly eliminates the duplicate code that was
deliberately left in place during EC review to avoid major
churn of the diskfile module prior to the kilo release.

This focuses on obvious de-duplication and shuffling code
between classes. It deliberately does not attempt to
hammer out every last piece of de-duplication where that
would introduce more complex changes - that can come later.

Code is moved from the module level and from ECDiskFile*
classes into new BaseDiskFile* classes.

Concrete classes for replication and EC policy retain their
existing names i.e. DiskFile[Manager|Writer|Reader|] and
ECDiskFile[Manager|Writer|Reader|] respectively.

Knock-on changes:

- fix bug whereby get_hashes was ignoring self.reclaim_age
  and always using the default arg value.

- replication diskfile manager now deletes a tombstone that is older
  than reclaim_age even when there is a newer .meta file.

- replication diskfile manager will no longer raise an
  AssertionError if only a .meta file is found during
  hash_cleanup_listdir.

- fix stale test in test_auditor.py: test_with_tombstone test
  setup was convoluted (probably dates back to when object puts
  did not clean up the object dir). Now that they do you have to
  try harder to create a dir with a tombstone and a data file.

Change-Id: I963e0d0ae0d6569ad1de605034c529529cbb4f9a

commit_message:
N1Kv: Fix failing network and port creates

Due to the change in name of an attribute from "profile_id" to "profile"
in Neutron attribute extensions for networks and ports, network and port
creations fail from the dashboard since dashboard is still using
"n1kv:profile_id" rather than "n1kv:profile".

Change-Id: I3a0508eda6b7b977d4f5bc5304d0ef13bd4092f2
Closes-Bug: 1474618
(cherry picked from commit b93e868925f4b81f763bd86d04853aaef3240b66)

commit_message:
line wrapping for longer ceph commands

Some of the ceph commands had gotten quite long, so reviewing them in
gerrit is a bit problematic. Do some line wrapping just to bring these
back to a bit more managable state.

Change-Id: Ice5122702f2466d059dd275b038d5ff983bcda44

commit_message:
Separate security_group_rules_client

As the qa-spec of consistent-service-method-names, we have decided
all service client modules will be separated into a single module
by each resource. So this patch separates security_group_rules_client
from security_groups_client.

Partially implements blueprint consistent-service-method-names

Change-Id: I28fab7730f62606c771631faf94203dbdd517358

commit_message:
Provisioner: use the correct bootstrap profile

In MOS 7.0 several bootstrap images and corresponding cobbler profiles
can exist. astute should use the correct profile name.

Partial-Bug: #1479882
UpgradeImpact: added 'bootstrap_profile' to astuted.conf
Change-Id: I844e30311938fcd2c0aea6f558862205ba2a9982

commit_message:
Keystone project role REST is broken

There is an extra white space in the REST url making it impossible to reach
the endpoint. Removing the white space will fix this issue.

Change-Id: Ic49d3821c0bc266a13522723323bda74a27f0389
Closes-Bug: #1479551

commit_message:
Remove duplicated check env code

Remove duplicated check environment code, use verify_env decorator or
check_env from utils. Note that tenant checks now return 403 instead 
of 401.

Closes-Bug: #1479570
Change-Id: I1964a9933394df133ab0559542f0c5dafd56e9a6

commit_message:
go: make replicateDevice more defensive

If anything causes replicateDevice to panic, log that.

Also close the window where panics could cause it to not release the
concurrency semaphore.

Open a debug http port so we can profile, get stack traces, etc.

commit_message:
Prepare for unicode enums from Oslo

This tweaks our object version hash test a little bit. Oslo is getting
ready to coerce all Enum valid_values to unicode (which is what we should
have done in the first place). That will have no real runtime effect on
us, but our version hashes will all fail the minute we start running with
that code, just because of the way repr() signals unicode strings. This
just adds a hack to our test to pre-encode them to UTF-8 before we compare
them (on py2). On py3, everything is unicode already, so this doesn't
change anything there.

In the long(er) run, our Enum implementation will go away, and our test
that does the hash calculation will go away. So, this is mostly just a dance
to avoid us breaking the gate soon.

Change-Id: Ie20377e86134a5e8b68a93a08c26ed6f3025ae9d

commit_message:
Python 3: enable test_metering_plugin

Two issues were preventing the tests from succeeding:
- a common "list/dict_values" issue with dictionaries;
- a call to "sorted" with a list of dictionaries as argument: this fails since
  dictionaries cannot be compared in Python 3.

Change-Id: I7ca80349bd9d0b6fe6dbd96bee7e7ea456ada325
Blueprint: neutron-python3

(2 comments)

one nit comment, but LGTM'}, {'account_id': 2750, 'date': '2015-07-29 17:50:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 2750, 'date': '2015-07-29 17:51:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

this seems like a much better approach. The details of the lock can be exposed in a new servers/{ID}/lock resource in Mitaka.'}, {'account_id': 782, 'date': '2015-07-29 17:53:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 2750, 'date': '2015-07-29 17:55:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 782, 'date': '2015-07-29 18:01:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2

This looks good.

I think we should give this an exception, given the problems it has hit.

I think we could be clearer that locked means "there is a lock", not "its locked for you", but thats fine.'}, {'account_id': 5441, 'date': '2015-07-30 22:10:10.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

It's unclear to me why this is better than exposing locked_by.  I understand that locked_by: null seem strange but we could just conditionally expose locked_by in the response only if it's set right?  I'm not against this since I agree with Sean that the concept of a lock will likely be expanded into something more reasonable later, just curious as this provides no real explanation for why this is being done."}, {'account_id': 8556, 'date': '2015-07-30 23:56:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Thanks Laski For review.

As discussed on IRC, lock seems good candidate for separate resource (as mentioned in spec something servers/server_id/lock) and their details (currently only who locked the server + new expanded details) can be exposed from new resource. 

So server details shows only concrete information like whether it is locked or not and lock detail can be fetched separately.

If we are not going for separate resource for lock detail than locked_by would be good enough in server details.

Not sure if that answer your concern.'}, {'account_id': 5441, 'date': '2015-07-31 11:45:28.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1

That helps me understand, thanks.  It would be nice if that was in the spec or commit message though.

Looking at the state of things now it seems that locked_by is concrete information as well and I'm still not sure I see the harm in exposing it as such.  But I do see that keeping the exposure simple with True/False does allow for us to change the implementation of lock later to not be reliant on locked_by if that's the direction we want to go. commit_message:
Fixing lock information spec for latest updates

There are some changes about publishing the lock information.

This patch capture and updates those in lock spec.

Implements blueprint add-locking-information-in-server-get-response

Change-Id: I5be664c3e99adc37738f8b074f1891dad97497b1

commit_message:
Instruction for building Fedora Atomic image

For Magnum development, we use a Fedora Atomic image prebuilt with a certain
version of Docker, Kubernetes, etcd and flannel.  The image does need to be
updated from time to time, or a user might want to test a specific version.
This document contains the instruction to build the image.
Optionally, you can also update the existing image.

Co-Authored-By: Steven Dake <stdake@cisco.com>
Change-Id: I62003abfa9077dad07988ecbce8fc5bd566f2299

commit_message:
go: fix expecttransport memory usage

DumpRequestOut wasn't really working.  It's meant to be a debugging function,
and it just writes the whole request, body and all, into a buffer, then strips
out the headers.  That means it can use a ton of memory.  So this just
serializes the request ourselves, which is bad and ugly, but at least it kind
of works.

Change-Id: Iafd4ec8bf7ffbf2506310722853b055d422228f1

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-07-28 18:13:05.000000000', 'message': 'Allow v3 identity to work without the admin domain name

The problem was that the value of admin_domain_name was required in order to
use identity v3 even if no admin was being used.

A new option auth.default_credentials_domain_name, with a non-None default,
is used instead of admin_domain_name except when requesting admin creds.
Because tenant_isolation and pre-provisioned credentials are mutually
exclusive, and to avoid having too many config options, the new option is
used instead of tenant_isolation_domain_name as well.

Change-Id: I52f0d4c0cc7e5eafa896776b12315ed6154dfae2
'}, {'created': '2015-07-29 15:27:15.000000000', 'message': "Allow v3 identity to work without the admin domain name

The problem was that the value of admin_domain_name was required in order to
use identity v3 even if no admin was being used.

A new option auth.default_credentials_domain_name
is used instead of admin_domain_name except when requesting admin creds.
This defaults to 'Default' which is the name keystone uses for compatibility
with v2.
Because tenant_isolation and pre-provisioned credentials are mutually
exclusive, and to avoid having too many config options, the new option is
used instead of tenant_isolation_domain_name as well.

Change-Id: I52f0d4c0cc7e5eafa896776b12315ed6154dfae2
"}]
commit_message:
Allow v3 identity to work without the admin domain name

The problem was that the value of admin_domain_name was required in order to
use identity v3 even if no admin was being used.

A new option auth.default_credentials_domain_name
is used instead of admin_domain_name except when requesting admin creds.
This defaults to 'Default' which is the name keystone uses for compatibility
with v2.
Because tenant_isolation and pre-provisioned credentials are mutually
exclusive, and to avoid having too many config options, the new option is
used instead of tenant_isolation_domain_name as well.

Change-Id: I52f0d4c0cc7e5eafa896776b12315ed6154dfae2

commit_message:
Fixes a docstring to reflect actual return values

RuleProcessor._verify_all_requirements can return None and in fact a
None is expected when there are no valid requirements.

Change-Id: I7559cf966115ab19e466e2df172b5165d9af1346

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-07-21 10:02:21.000000000', 'message': "Change default getaddrinfo(3) behaviour when IPv6 not configured

This patch address issue caused by failed connections to IPv6
hosts when dual stack IPv6 configuration is not finished or doesn't
work. The default is to take precedence on IPv6 resolved hosts as
described in RFC3484. This causes problem to download packages from
v6 enabled repositories and may cause many other connection timeouts.

Change-Id: I9d2236d6ba7550819314923f0943ac5270ce7842
Closes-bug: #1451899
"}]
commit_message:
Change default getaddrinfo(3) behaviour when IPv6 not configured

This patch address issue caused by failed connections to IPv6
hosts when dual stack IPv6 configuration is not finished or doesn't
work. The default is to take precedence on IPv6 resolved hosts as
described in RFC3484. This causes problem to download packages from
v6 enabled repositories and may cause many other connection timeouts.

Change-Id: I9d2236d6ba7550819314923f0943ac5270ce7842
Closes-bug: #1451899

commit_message:
Remove source packages from fwm yum repo

Seems we don't need this any more because
perestroika puts source packages on its own.
They are available online for users.
Besides, perestroika has slightly different
repo format than fwm repo and switching
to perestroika  breaks src rpm downloading
for staging mirror job.

Change-Id: Ifef8e37b690dc1d867cad023fa138144637f689e

subject: Some parameter in heat template should be string
messages:
[{'account_id': 12385, 'date': '2015-07-28 10:30:38.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 12053, 'date': '2015-07-28 11:18:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 12053, 'date': '2015-07-28 11:23:55.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Heat template has Boolean type, it's better to use it."}, {'account_id': 12385, 'date': '2015-07-28 12:58:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Actually, "flannel_use_vxlan" parameter is used at below

* https://github.com/openstack/magnum/blob/a394225e3bc44b7dc1545a2e1a3a83d60bf9b900/magnum/templates/heat-kubernetes/fragments/configure-flannel.sh#L8

And, "kube_allow_priv" parameter is used at below

* https://github.com/openstack/magnum/blob/a394225e3bc44b7dc1545a2e1a3a83d60bf9b900/magnum/templates/heat-kubernetes/fragments/configure-kubernetes-master.sh#L11

These parameters should not be "True" or "False" but just "true" or "false" .  so we must use these parameter as "string", because if we use Boolean value for this purpose, parameter values change to "True" or "False".'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-07-28 17:05:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

commit_message:
Some parameter in heat template should be string

Below parameters in kubecluster.yaml and kubeminion.yaml should be
string instead of boolean.

* flannel_use_vxlan
* kube_allow_priv

This patch fixes it.

Change-Id: I91c17505af9083ddf4828b8e51a045c3474ec88c
Closes-bug: #1478890

commit_message:
tests: functional tests for keypairs create in API microversion 2.7

Adding functional tests to cover keypairs creation in API
API microversion 2.7

Also, corrected NoAuthMiddlewareV3 to set always_admin to False
as it should follow the same functionality as noauth2.

Related to blueprint admin-query-any-keypair

Change-Id: I44c0a8c1623c6c0d3363842b62afb87f6c1503da

commit_message:
Should change 'injected_file_content_bytes' into 'injected_file_size'

openstack quota set --injected-file-size 11 testproject_dx,
Because in python-openstackclient/openstackclient/common/quota.py
in COMPUTE_QUOTAS 'injected_file_content_bytes': 'injected-file-size'
We should change 'injected_file_content_bytes' to 'injected_file_size'.

Partial-Bug: #1475831
Change-Id: I4880a4c5a7d6a36b75e6a0ae3766a131b7ca1649

commit_message:
Python 3: Use use_unicode=1 under Python 3

Setting use_unicode=1 allows DBAPI to handle the encoding and decoding of unicode.

We can see the details from the following url.
http://docs.sqlalchemy.org/en/rel_0_9/dialects/mysql.html#unicode-encoding-decoding

Change-Id: I4bb67d9c8a439ee18acdcf227140dfff1a70cd93
Closes-Bug: #1479313

local_settings file using variable "OPENSTACK_HYPERVISOR_FEATURE",

commit_message:
[compute-system-admin]Fix the wrong variable in the inject password section

Now the Dashboard disable the password fields by editing the dashboard's
local_settings file using variable "OPENSTACK_HYPERVISOR_FEATURE",
actually the variable is "OPENSTACK_HYPERVISOR_FEATURES"

This patch fix it

Change-Id: I84bc2aefebf90ec2f505c37332cac5cd4b1d258f

commit_message:
Remove 'name' from explicit fields in object model

* Generate 'name' field automatically and insert
  it to the last (management) form;
  Since management form with the name field should be browsed
  all the time, conditional dictionary and 'drop_wm_form' flag,
  which controls the form appearance, are no longer necessary.
  In this commit conditional dict and drop_wm_form are dropped.
  But 'stay_at_the_catalog' checkbox is appeared in case application
  creation form was called directly from the catalog and it's not
  a dependency application, in case application was called via '+'
  this checkbox is not needed. It is managed by manage_workflow.js

* Insert 'name' to the object model header;

* Get name field from object model header or directly from object modal;

* Add name function to the YAQL context;

* Optimize application creation wizard;

The specification is located at:
http://murano-specs.readthedocs.org/en/latest/specs/liberty/dynamic-ui-specify-no-explicit-name-field.html

Implements blueprint dynamic-ui-specify-no-explicit-name-field
Change-Id: I3bcbdcb14198990033489d27f5ebc72c4184bc5a

commit_message:
Make glance and heat share a common schema.

This makes a common schema based on heat and glance's schemas,
laying the groundwork for additional types in the future. It
also modifies the website and entries to match.

Change-Id: I8d439dccc7f75c6a9b5e95e5094353f08e88e655

[{'created': '2015-06-02 16:46:32.000000000', 'message': "Remove sphinx_config.init_values() manual call

The function signature for Sphinx's config.init_values() changed since
version 1.3. That leads to:

TypeError: init_values() takes exactly 2 arguments (1 given)

But the function is already correctly called from
application.Sphinx()'s constructor. So use the configuration object
from the application instead of creating an own config object.

Change-Id: I343c26560bfe5116d5348b50b1890b3442ed845a
Closes-Bug: #1379998
"}]
commit_message:
Remove sphinx_config.init_values() manual call

The function signature for Sphinx's config.init_values() changed since
version 1.3. That leads to:

TypeError: init_values() takes exactly 2 arguments (1 given)

But the function is already correctly called from
application.Sphinx()'s constructor. So use the configuration object
from the application instead of creating an own config object.

Change-Id: I343c26560bfe5116d5348b50b1890b3442ed845a
Closes-Bug: #1379998

commit_message:
Scope db_list calls to ports of interest

_restore_local_vlan_map and _bind_devices in the OVS agent
only need to operate on a specific set of ports that it already
knows before calling db_list. This patch updates the db_list call
for each to use the ports the functions are operating on.

This prevents the db_list call from trying to retrieve info in completely
unrelated ports that could be being operated on/deleted concurrently.

Closes-Bug: #1475252
Change-Id: I75bfb9c0abf65173e64f413c6f7f201bc353803f

commit_message:
Mount share API

Adds API and operations for mounting Manila shares to clusters at
both the cluster and node group level.

Implements: blueprint mount-share-api
Change-Id: I98fd1b97f4639161396ab44ebcb1508fca648a06

commit_message:
libvirt: do relative block rebase only with non-null base

You can't use VIR_DOMAIN_BLOCK_REBASE_RELATIVE with null
base, libvirt reports error in this case, so check if
base is non-null before setting this flag (relative argument
of BlockDevice.rebase method).

The error was introduced by commit
e9639913294036ff94f354e9c8ea18cd816243ab

Change-Id: Ife50f211fd54190a2665ad090f6208048b841690
Closes-Bug: #1475202

commit_message:
Install HAProxy 1.5 on Ubuntu Devstack

Currently HAProxy 1.4 is being installed but need to have
HAProxy 1.5 in order to have a working implementation of
tls termination.

Change-Id: Icac342a20d31731310b776ae71ba7c43e660315b

commit_message:
Remove non-voting job from networking-odl

gate-tempest-dsvm-networking-odl is non-voting - and non-voting gate
jobs are just wasting resources. Remove the job from the gate.
It can be readded once the job is voting.

Change-Id: I586a5988cd232e47d3f6f9b4f73bcda674e9d4dc

Tempest tests for Listener using testscenarios

1. This test is moved to the 'ddt' directory.

2. It tests the following scenarios in the Neutron-LBaaS API using the
REST client for Listener:

 |------------------|------------------|-------------------------|
 |Action            |LB admin_state_up | Listener admin_state_up |
 |------------------|------------------|-------------------------|
 | Create Listener  | True             | True                    |
 |                  | True             | False                   |
 |                  | False            | True                    |
 |                  | False            | False                   |
 | Update Listener  | True             | True  --> True          |
 |                  | True             | True  --> False         |
 |                  | True             | False --> True          |
 |                  | True             | False --> False         |
 |                  | False            | True  --> True          |
 |                  | False            | True  --> False         |
 |                  | False            | False --> True          |
 |                  | False            | False --> False         |
 |------------------|------------------|-------------------------|

commit_message:
pass environment variables of proxy to tox

When a development environment is under a proxy, tox is failed even if
environment variables of the proxy are set.

This patch fix this problem.

Change-Id: I07bc516608bd7f6dedbc9f228ecae560a405993d

commit_message:
functions: allow to run cleanup_host outside of devstack context

This is an initiative to be able to run cleanup_host function outside a
devstack run.
Example: when running Puppet OpenStack modules on a node, being able to
run cleanup_host function so we can get the machine logs like the same
way it's done in Devstack.

This patch does not change anything when running devstack, it just
sanitize some copy/paste by checking if the file/dir exists before.
Otherwise, it add Puppet supports.

To build $PROJECTS, we list the modules installed in /etc/puppet/modules
(this is the only way I found to make it dynamically).
That way, if not running Devstack, we will check if /var/log/<project>
exists and copy logs from there.

Change-Id: Ic10032893785b52c524957f2d44ee0d2823a0c49

commit_message:
EDP Spark jobs work with Swift

1) Fixed the path to hadoop-swift.jar - in cloudera
   it's named as hadoop-openstack.jar
2) Fixed the options for launch wrapper with yarn-cluster
   (more details at http://spark.apache.org/docs/latest/running-on-yarn.html
    'Important notes' section).
3) Fixed the issue of swift credentials visibility in Yarn cluster.
4) Fixed related unit-test with the same error in it.

Change-Id: I5e8c72f0e362792f06245b3744a32342abc42389
Closes-bug: 1474128

commit_message:
Catch ObjectDeletedError and skip port or subnet removal

When network is deleted service ports are deleted in the scope of
delete_network. Service ports could also be deleted by other entities
such as DHCP agent releasing dhcp port.
That could rarely lead to a race condition when port object used in
_delete_ports helper is already deleted causing ObjectDeletedError
exception.
Need to handle it and prevent object deletion in that case.

Change-Id: I531251d3211545c82a5bb7a471b7915da9b763b7
Closes-Bug: #1454408

commit_message:
test_db_base_plugin_v2: Improve DBReferenceError generation

The current coding, raising DBReferenceError directly, seems to
confuse sqlalchemy a bit.  Instead, actually causes the error by
tweaking the row being inserted.

Change-Id: I17ec6dab19b0e573675559042b7529f7bdd2671b

commit_message:
Remove {{ from "with_items" and "when" statements

This patch resolves a minor issue that was generating a "warning"
message when running the galera-install.yml playbook.

The "{{" and "}}" are not required for conditionals, and loop
expressions, so these can and should safely be removed from "when:"
statements and "with_items:" statements.

Functionality does not change but the warning message will go away after
this patch.

Change-Id: I3e9d3a4afb0e3d1284c78a37dba6d1534154a063
Closes-Bug: #1475328
(cherry picked from commit 57577bb369a107ed704f4791090b1c810599258c)

commit_message:
Properly use groups throught Ansible

Additionally, make each service optional witha config option allowing
for extreme flexibility should the deployer want to replace a service
with a non-kolla one (the database for example).

Change-Id: I7b644da7cfa7e8e6b6878eb1b1aa97db830504ae

commit_message:
Rename role name to service name

The original purpose for having an abstract like 'database' rather than
the service name of 'mariadb' has been change. Our direction is different
and this patch reflects consistent naming throughout

Change-Id: I704896191cc5243f9dab2a4cca9120e9dc2ceb2c
Closes-Bug: #1478328

commit_message:
Layout fixes for dashboard

 - closing rename control on outside click
 - spacing issues fix
 - fix for disappearing 'No nodes' warning
 - spacing issues fixes
 - fix for 'not-allowed' cursor
 - added check for network verification task in progress

Closes-bug: #1479403

Change-Id: Ia7600340be5f6282cf345b82ddcf93bf582b37d1

Cinder is unique in that interaction with the volumes
must occur in the container as opposed to from the host.
This doc will lay out a guide for Cinder and useful

Change-Id: I5cdff42ba3a40c1a20a11570649ac42a1c3aa837

commit_message:
Add a doc for Cinder

Cinder is unique in that interaction with the volumes
must occur in the container as opposed to from the host.
This doc will lay out a guide for Cinder and useful
debugging tips.

Change-Id: I5cdff42ba3a40c1a20a11570649ac42a1c3aa837

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be

commit_message:
Add stable compat jobs to trove-integration repo

The trove-integration repo is branchless and is used in runs against
kilo, juno, and master. However commits are only checked against
master, this leaves a huge target on the stable branches' back.

Change-Id: I37ea58a4a8242a24632e0f539f9bd204d7530019

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-06-26 14:24:40.000000000', 'message': 'Fix saving tz aware datetimes in Versioned Objects

Currently we cannot save date fields in Versioned Objects because they
are timezone aware and our database is not.

If we look at our objects definition, we are not giving any value to
tzinfo_aware argument, so it takes DateTime default value (True).

In our sqlalchemy model definitions we are defining our datetime fields
as Colum(DateTime) which will take sqlalchemy default: class
sqlalchemy.types.DateTime(timezone=False)

In most cases we are accessing those fields directly through the DB
methods, so we don't see the problem, but if we were to modify any of
those fields using versioned object, for example scheduled_at, and then
save the object we'll get an exception:

 File ".../sqlalchemy/sql/type_api.py", line 278, in compare_values
 return x == y
 TypeError: can't compare offset-naive and offset-aware datetimes

Because we are trying to save a timezone aware date to a timezone
unaware DB field.

This patch changes how method obj_get_changes returns datefields for
saving. It makes them timezone naive and transform them to UTC timezone.

Change-Id: Ie7b0249e3f6850e7c70d23fc53cfaf27fe04afbb
Closes-Bug: #1469120
'}, {'created': '2015-06-29 13:18:05.000000000', 'message': 'Fix saving tz aware datetimes in Versioned Objects

 TypeError: can't compare offset-naive and offset-aware datetimes

Following Dan's advice we create a specific cinder_obj_get_changes,

commit_message:
Fix saving tz aware datetimes in Versioned Objects

Currently we cannot save date fields in Versioned Objects because they
are timezone aware and our database is not.

If we look at our objects definition, we are not giving any value to
tzinfo_aware argument, so it takes DateTime default value (True).

In our sqlalchemy model definitions we are defining our datetime fields
as Column(DateTime) which will take sqlalchemy default: class
sqlalchemy.types.DateTime(timezone=False)

In most cases we are accessing those fields directly through the DB
methods, so we don't see the problem, but if we were to modify any of
those fields using versioned object, for example scheduled_at, and then
save the object we'll get an exception:

 File ".../sqlalchemy/sql/type_api.py", line 278, in compare_values
 return x == y
 TypeError: can't compare offset-naive and offset-aware datetimes

Because we are trying to save a timezone aware date to a timezone
unaware DB field.

Following Dan's advice we create a specific cinder_obj_get_changes,
instead of overwriting obj_get_changes, that returns all datefields as
timezone naive UTC datetimes ready for saving.

Change-Id: Ie7b0249e3f6850e7c70d23fc53cfaf27fe04afbb
Closes-Bug: #1469120

commit_message:
Update link to baremetal provisioning

The link to baremetal under the hypervisors section of the Cloud Administrator Guide
points to a depreciated page for nova baremetal, instructing users to go to the Ironic
baremetal provisioning page instead.

The fix updates the baremetal link within the Cloud Admin Guide rst 
and xml files to go directly to the Ironic page.

Change-Id: Ia8607a84832b1f53ad54d38e75b1687d579da0eb
Closes-Bug: #1478628

commit_message:
Fix rspec 3.x syntax

- Convert 'should' keyword to 'is_expected.to'
- The old ':should' syntax in rspec 3.x is deprecated in favor of
  ':expect' syntax.
- Operator matchers:
  '1.should == 1' into 'expect(1).to eq(1)'

Change-Id: I84b993065a00f5b5c55bd6834c6d54bc57c249e0
Signed-off-by: Gael Chamoulaud <gchamoul@redhat.com>
(cherry picked from commit 18960407918cfbea3e9ca6ff1f1384429471c27f)

commit_message:
v3: make sure default domain is created before any other resource

When using Keystone v3 and domains, we need to make sure the default
domain (if its name if not 'Default') is created before any other
domain scoped resource.

By creating a new anchor, we can add the requirement in Keystone types
that need this dependency.
If the default domain name is not modified, the Anchor won't be in the
catalog but it's not an issue when using 'autorequire' in Puppet types.

This patch also change the default domains in acceptance tests, so we
can actually test the feature and make sure resources are created after
having the default domain created.

Change-Id: I2870eaa98f816c92df901ed2fa92e8db89b67656
Closes-bug: #1478037
(cherry picked from commit 50059b6c470623bc2cf315861c7ba2a28b8954c4)

Add config parameters to run Keystone v3 tests

Allow to configure uri_v3, auth_version and admin_domain_name in identity section.
Required when enabling keystone v3 tests.

commit_message:
Switch all the yaml files to share the same root object type

This will allow easier merging of all the assets into one file.
It also fixes a bug where schema's were not enforcing on heat
and glance. It fixes the glance entries to validate.

Change-Id: I710e8348423aa0b6c09506b9daf58f4b8cc882b4

commit_message:
acceptance: run keystone in a WSGI server

Running keystone via eventlet is deprecated as of Kilo in favor of
running in a WSGI server (e.g. mod_wsgi).
Support for keystone under eventlet will be removed in the "M"-Release.

This patch test an upgrade between eventlet to wsgi.
In the future, the eventlet test will be dropped in favor of wsgi which
will be default.

Change-Id: Ieb07473725fbd51aac45e90c9aac1e819b944ee0
(cherry picked from commit 9e0cd4c37e49813e6f4a1b1fee3bbfc610f15f1a)

commit_message:
Ironic: Better handle InstanceNotFound on destroy()

After telling Ironic to delete the instance the destroy() code in the
Ironic nova driver keeps waiting for the provision state of that node
to change. If the instance have been already cleaned up in Ironic the
nova code should just ignore it and continue. This also skip trying to
update the node to remove the instance association if the instance was
already removed in Ironic.

Missing unittests to the _unprovision() method were added as part of
this patch since it touches it.

Closes-Bug: #1436568
Change-Id: I0b1b710056d48c8b7bb2b46fdaba192922926420

commit_message:
Add tempest::config class

Other modules provide an X::config class to be able to specify
parameters that are not yet part of the module. Tempest was missing this
feature. This commit aims to add it for puppet-tempest.

Change-Id: Ib9ebd3569eeb42a1a5b4b2173253264e767d904b
(cherry picked from commit c46af79ab7781605a26f9b52d37577dfa1b57050)

commit_message:
Avoid adding 1 to a failure (if it gets triggered)

Sometimes the CI gate times out and instead of returning
normal results a failure object is returned, so be more
careful on adding integers to those objects.

Closes-Bug: 1478744

Change-Id: Ibdb9d30266d2a7f3bfeacc39e74cf61b44025a56

commit_message:
Replace the tree 'pformat()' recursion with non-recursive variant

This adjusted variant creates the same output but is hopefully
easier to understand and follow than the recursive version.

This version is also not limited by the python stack limit which
is a general good thing to avoid being limited by.

It also adds a bunch of tests to make sure the format is as expected
under various tree structures.

Change-Id: I2ae42c7c1bf72794800929250bcf6ccbe658230b

commit_message:
[WIP] BGP Dynamic Routing: adding BGP driver

Add the driver interface and the Ryu's BGP speaker implementation.
All communication starts in the agent and the Neutron API just responds
to these calls.

In the Neutron API two new methods are added to handle agent's calls: one
for send the advertise routes and the other one to receive the
discovered routes. These discovered routes are passed to
routinginstance's associated routers and saved into extraroutes database
table.

Co-Author: tfukushima <tfukushima@midokura.com>
Co-Author: Vikram Choudhary <vikram.choudhary@huawei.com>

Partially-Implements: blueprint bgp-dynamic-routing
Signed-off-by: Jaume Devesa <devvesa@gmail.com>

Change-Id: Ic9ddd8523ca5a3cf99ab4027c112ec9f9872a3d8

[WIP] BGP Dynamic Routing neutronclient changes

Neutron client changes for BGP functionality.
All the changes can are defined in the blueprint bgp-dynamic-routing

[{'created': '2014-08-20 14:43:32.000000000', 'message': 'BGP dynamic routing: adding agent and scheduling

Dynamic routing needs a new agent that will host the BGP speaker driver
and will do the actual communication between BGP peers.

This agent will take information from a single Routing Instance entity,
that has all the information that the agent needs to do the routing
exchange: peers and routes. In this approach, an agent can only host one
Routing Instance to avoid conflicts.

This commit intruduces a dummy agent that auto-registers to Neutron API
and send keep-alive messages.

A binding between the agent and the routing instance is mandatory in the
database and also the api endpoints to let the user
associate/disassociate a routing instante to an agent.

There is also an autoscheduling feature that will assign a routing
instance to the first agent that asks for synchronization. Default
scheduler class will only assign non-assigned routing instances to
agents. HA feature (two agents hosting the same routing instance) has to
be done manually.

Partially-Implements: blueprint bgp-dynamic-routing
Change-Id: I33adafef54be37a14fcccaf2985618bf89e3a154

commit_message:
[WIP] BGP Dynamic Routing: adding agent and scheduling

Dynamic routing needs a new agent that will host the BGP speaker driver
and will do the actual communication between BGP peers.

This agent will take information from a single Routing Instance entity,
that has all the information that the agent needs to do the routing
exchange: peers and routes. In this approach, an agent can only host one
Routing Instance to avoid conflicts.

This commit intruduces a dummy agent that auto-registers to Neutron API
and send keep-alive messages.

A binding between the agent and the routing instance is mandatory in the
database and also the api endpoints to let the user
associate/disassociate a routing instante to an agent.

There is also an autoscheduling feature that will assign a routing
instance to the first agent that asks for synchronization. Default
scheduler class will only assign non-assigned routing instances to
agents. HA feature (two agents hosting the same routing instance) has to
be done manually.

Partially-Implements: blueprint bgp-dynamic-routing
Change-Id: I33adafef54be37a14fcccaf2985618bf89e3a154

commit_message:
Refactoring logging and translations on freezer_api

Refactoring logging to use oslo.log to have standard OpenStack logging.
Refactoring log messages to enable i18n translations.
Refactoring Exception messages to enable i18n translations.

New requirement oslo.log.

[{'account_id': 17578, 'date': '2015-07-30 18:45:48.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 10068, 'date': '2015-07-30 18:45:53.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC
    Workflow: http://docs.openstack.org/infra/manual/developers.html

from the common agent library, since that library imports the linux utils

commit_message:
Linux Bridge Agent: Import utils via neutron.agent.common

Just a toe in the water, but the Linux Bridge agent should be importing
from the common agent library, since that library imports the linux utils
in turn. This reflects the same behavior of the OVS agent.

This is a base patch for further work, to explore if the Linux Bridge
agent can use more of the code in the neutron.agent.common namespace,
like the polling module.

Change-Id: I92241af74bdd2cce58d596ffbfc2a92129d10c41
Related-Bug: #1468803

commit_message:
pass environment variables of proxy to tox

When a development environment is under a proxy, tox is failed even if
environment variables of the proxy are set.

This patch fix this problem.

Change-Id: I5ee361ba54b296eee2336214ca6b0559c6190af8

commit_message:
Neutron Tun support

New tests:
* deploy_neutron_tun
* deploy_neutron_tun_ha
* deploy_neutron_tun_ha_with_public_network
Removed:
* deploy_neutron_gre
* deploy_neutron_gre_ha_with_public_network
Set as deprecated:
* deploy_neutron_tun_ha
New env var NEUTRON_SEGMENT option 'tun'

Change-Id: I582990c703609c3ee765b966a2d4c3629423267d
Related-Bug: #1479392

[{'created': '2015-07-28 21:46:27.000000000', 'message': 'Remove unused server functions

These functions are used neither in the Ansible modules, nor in the
nodepool code. Their existence is confusing as they serve no purpose
other than to add extra attributes to the server dict. The Ansible
modules are doing this by invoking meta.get_hostvars_from_server()
directly. Ideally, they would not need to do that and we would
automatically normalize the server dict and add those extra hostvar
variables in get_server() so that we have a single view of the
server dict. That may be a later change.

As for get_server_meta() and the comment there, I cannot find this
method being used in either the latest devel branch, or in the
current release (stable-1.9 branch).

commit_message:
Remove unused server functions

These functions are used neither in the Ansible modules, nor in the
nodepool code. Their existence is confusing as they serve no purpose
other than to add extra attributes to the server dict. They are
holdovers from when we still returned server objects, not dicts.

Change-Id: I06e5c2b7bfe3ba098016d5348e41e7002b361e6c

commit_message:
Process config options via os-client-config

Assume that a cloud config object will be passed in. For compat,
create one and pass in kwargs if it's not - but based the internal
operation on the existence of a cloud_config object.

Change-Id: I31b2d851e0636c7742468aa62565295a2c5266e2
Depends-On: I8764ed68f8a38563c4242d4b50e2158e99ed4109

commit_message:
Remove extra runner layer and just use use machine in engine

Just directly use the built machine in the action engine and
avoid having another layer of abstraction that does not provide
that much value. This makes the code cleaner, and more easy to
understand (and so-on).

Change-Id: Iae1279098112254338258c1941c15889f1ad1a79

commit_message:
Pass socket timeout to swiftclient

Needs a release of swiftclient containing the depended-on patch.

We're passing timeout to everyone else now, so for consistency, we
should pass it to swiftclient too.

Depends-On: I699ebb1e092aa010af678de7ba15712da6ed5315
Change-Id: I864403e0ac32f2645026dd13189a03cb9b0eeb01

commit_message:
UCS: node-get-boot-device is failing for Cisco servers

The UCS to Ironic key mapping for supported boot devices was changed
in UcsSdk v0.8.2.2. As a result of that, UCS drivers are failing while
looking at the UCS to Ironic mapping devices dict.

This change would address this problem.

Change-Id: Id86c4e2a7dfde552f808fcf83baba4097d9fd0c5
Closes-Bug: #1478452

commit_message:
Support keystone v3 domains in swift-dispersion

This provides the capability to specify a project_name,
project_domain_name and user_domain_name in /etc/swift/dispersion.conf.
If this values are set in dispersion.conf they get populated to the
swift-client.  With this it is possible to have a specific dispersion
project specified, which is not the keystone default domain.  Changes
were applied to swift-dispersion-populate and swift-dispersion-report.
Relevant man pages, the example dispersion.conf and the admin guide were
updated accordingly.

DocImpact
Closes-Bug: #1468374

Change-Id: I0e716f8d281b4d0f510bc568bcee4a13fc480ff7

(3 comments)

Forgive me if I'm wrong, because I know nothing of Ceilometer and notifications, but from I could read I don't think these notifications are going to get into Ceilometer if we don't update Cinder's bus listener agent adding them to even_types: https://github.com/openstack/ceilometer/blob/master/ceilometer/volume/notifications.py#L53

So there should be a patch to Ceilometer that adds these new notifications, and in this commit message a Depends-On for the other patch or at least a mention to keep them linked.

As for exceptions I would expect them to be notified to Ceilometer in some way, but I can't seem to find how."}, {'account_id': 8846, 'date': '2015-07-01 02:00:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

commit_message:
Notify the transfer volume action in cinder

Now when we transfer a volume, there is not corresponding action
notification that is sent to ceilometer. Include the actions of create,
accept and delete.

The bp that this patch implements, proposes adding those action to enrich
the notification in cinder.

Notify is added in Create, Accept, and Delete actions.

Change-Id: I9d71c55d103cc501f60585b64902d364af21d4d9
Implements:  blueprint notify-the-transfer-volume-action-in-cinder

commit_message:
Change os_auth_url to use identity_endpoint in conf template

Current template ceilometer.conf.erb is using auth_uri for os_auth_url
which is not a correct approach. This auth_uri is dedicated to be used
by auth_uri under section [keystone_authtoken]. On the other hand, the
passed in identity_endpoint param is not used. Actually, by comparison
with other cookbooks, identity_endpoint should be used for keystone
identity service connection.

Change-Id: I50c631000efe9c82cd83723c1bf9a7c6ef54556c
Closes-bug: #1479399

why add Exxx ignore when it's not needed? it's working now"}, {'account_id': 9107, 'date': '2015-07-28 11:42:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

(1 comment)

Alistair Coles wrote:
> -1 because of the change to ignore some Exxx that previously were selected.

I only ignore *new* errors.

> I don't (yet) understand the rationale of changing from whitelist to blacklist - before we selected individually, now we ignore individually. Is that a *requirement* of the newer hacking version or just a style choice?

Two things. First, I chose the same configuration than other OpenStack projects (nova, cinder, neutron, glance, etc.). All these projects use "ignore =" but not "select =" for flake8 in tox.ini.

Second, there is a technical limitation of pep8 (flake8 is based on pep8): if you use the "select" option, the "ignore" is simply ignored. Well, it looks like a bug, but I'm not interested to fix pep8.

Code ignoring the "ignore" option in pep8:

https://github.com/PyCQA/pep8/blob/d48eef071003952ed0f98445dc3dc6bc29618f9c/pep8.py#L1808

IMHO the good practice is more to explicitly ignore checks (new blacklist approach), than only running a few of them (old whitelist approach). The purpose of flake8 is to enhance the coding style, but also to help to detect common bugs.

For example, there are new checks to help the migration to Python 3. These Python 3 checks are currently ignored in my patch, we will fix them later. For example, janonymous already proposed a patch to fix the syntax of print() on Python 3.

> Also, I am confused by the behavior of e.g. H402 (one line docstring needs punctuation) ...

See my comment: H402 was simply removed from hacking 0.10.'}, {'account_id': 7847, 'date': '2015-07-28 13:18:24.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

It does appear that E251 has maybe become stricter in newer hacking/pep8 :/ (it fails where a line break splits a keyword arg assignment), and I can see that other projects have it disabled as a result (e.g. https://github.com/openstack/nova/blob/master/tox.ini#L132) but I think a better approach would be to fix new failures at same time as changing hacking version. commit_message:
Update hacking to 0.10.0

Replace the whitelist of flake8 checks (select) with a blacklist
(ignore).  It makes possible to disable a single check, which was not
possible before. This new approach permits to enable new tests more
easily and see which checks are currently disabled.

Only new checks are disabled, this change doesn't run less checks than
before. Currently, many checks are disabled, but following changes will
fix these new warnings.

When the "select" option of flake8 is used in tox.ini, the "ignore"
option is ignored. It is not possible to use "select" and "ignore"
options at the same time. See the code in pep8 (flake8 is based on
pep8):

https://github.com/PyCQA/pep8/blob/d48eef071003952ed0f98445dc3dc6bc29618f9c/pep8.py#L1808

The purpose of flake8 is to enhance the coding style, but also to help
to detect common bugs. Blacklisting checks permits to detect new bugs
when upgrading the tools. For example, new checks were recently added to
help porting code to Python 3.

This change permits to use pbr 1.0 and newer which is required to
support Python 3. Previously, hacking 0.8.1 was used, but hacking 0.8 is
incompatible with pbr 1.0 and newer (hacking 0.8 requires pbr<1.0).

pbr 1.0 is required to use environment markers on requirements to
install dnspython on Python 2 and dnspython3 on Python 3.

Change-Id: I41d63b9467083d7606ad18aaa398ca7738b27fae

Considering one of the scenarios, 
"1. Create load balancer with valid attributes and admin_state_up is set to True.
2. Create a listener with valid attributes and admin_state_up is set to False.
3. Verify that the status tree for operating status is set to ONLINE for load balancer and DISABLED for listener.
4. Verify all entities attributes are correct."

Our test should fail if either the lb's or the listener's status is not as expected. So I didn't bother testing the other when one fails. If anyone has other views, please let me know.'}, {'account_id': 12417, 'date': '2015-05-12 22:15:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

commit_message:
Tempest tests for Members using testscenarios

1. Moved this test from v2/api to v2/ddt.

2. It tests the create/update member method calls with various
combimations of values for the admin_state_up field of lb,
listener, pool and member.

Change-Id: I22edf551cff8543100ca23cf80532fdd6e01b8ea

[{'created': '2015-03-26 06:45:24.000000000', 'message': "Catch AttributeError at instance.info_cache.delete

When the instance has no related record in instance_info_caches,
an error has occurred ('NoneType' object has no attribute).
As a result, nova can't delete the instance.
Such an incomplete instance, should be deletable by nova.
So the root cause might be addressed separately, but this
exception should be caught and logged, ignored.

Change-Id: Ie0bba032615d3da06cdd95b221beb37a9b8a377d
Closes-bug: #1436693

commit_message:
Avoid AttributeError at instance.info_cache.delete

When the instance has no related record in instance_info_caches,
an error has occurred ('NoneType' object has no attribute).
As a result, nova can't delete the instance.
Such an incomplete instance, should be deletable by nova.
So the root cause might be addressed separately, but this
exception should be avoided and logged.

Change-Id: Ie0bba032615d3da06cdd95b221beb37a9b8a377d
Closes-bug: #1436693

commit_message:
VMware: add resource limits for disk

The flavor extra specs for quotas has been extended to support
 quota:disk_io_limit - The utilization of a virtual machine will not exceed
                       this limit. The unit is number of I/O per second.
 quota:disk_io_reservation -  Reservation control is used to provide guaranteed
                              allocation in terms of IOPS
 quota:disk_io_shares_level - the allocation level. This can be 'custom', 'high'
                              'normal' or 'low'.
 quota:disk_io_shares_share - in the event that 'custom' is used, this is the
                              number of shares.
This enables the VMware driver to enable disk allocations
for the running instance.

Please see http://goo.gl/6sHwIA for a detailed explanation of the above.

DocImpact

The is part of the blueprint vmware-limits

commit_message:
Fix cluster-resize operation param checking in server side

This patch fixes the bug1479586 by setting the default value of variable
desired located in ClusterAction.do_resize to cluster.desired_capacity.

Change-Id: I07b30da201a0a4482fb95770b012f4f0299a322a
Closes-Bug: #1479586

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-07-03 06:26:21.000000000', 'message': "Add a register-zanata-projects.py script

Currently, projects in Transifex are set up by hand, which requires
infrastructure members log into its admin interface and add projects.
With Zanata, we can do much better, so add a script that will parse
projects.yaml, and create any projects that are required.

Add 'translate: true' to projects.yaml for all projects configured in
the Zanata development instance.

This also refactors part of the code that ProjectConfig inside
ZanataUtils was using so that both scripts can leverage it.

Change-Id: Ic28d5dcfdd471dccbe406955a85dbc6f5d7335d1

commit_message:
Add a register-zanata-projects.py script and job

Currently, projects in Transifex are set up by hand, which requires
infrastructure members log into its admin interface and add projects.
With Zanata, we can do much better, so add a script that will parse
projects.yaml, and create any projects that are required.

Change-Id: Ic28d5dcfdd471dccbe406955a85dbc6f5d7335d1

commit_message:
make package install safer

The following makes apt-get install quite a bit safer by retrying the
apt-get update should it fail using a common pattern copied from
devstack.

It also keeps track of whether or not we've run the apt-get update
during this run, which means we don't it more than once for no reason.

For the specific case of the python yaml module we also check to see
if it's installed first (which it often is) to avoid doing network
actions when not needed.

This should make the

Related-Bug: #1400905

show up less often

Change-Id: I77159da4e33f4255bd8a5d7d8cd3eaae3a8a59a4

LGTM, thanks'}, {'account_id': 8959, 'date': '2015-07-30 14:07:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)

Thanks for the simplifying code. Worked well when tested but found a new bug while testing which existed before this patch. Since its the same code path, its better to update this patch instead of filing new bug after this merge.

The bug is - when you update an image with metadata by removing old properties and add new properties; the update doesn't remove the old properties.

Instead of using upsert, use index operation for both create and update. Here's the code diff with this patch using index operation which worked for me.

--- a/searchlight/elasticsearch/plugins/glance/images_notification_handler.py
+++ b/searchlight/elasticsearch/plugins/glance/images_notification_handler.py
@@ -50,10 +50,9 @@ class ImageHandler(base.NotificationBase):
         id = payload['id']
         payload = self.serialize_notification(payload)
         body = {
-            "doc": payload,
-            "doc_as_upsert": True
+            "doc": payload
         }
-        self.engine.update(
+        self.engine.index(
             index=self.index_name,
             doc_type=self.document_type,
             body=body,'}, {'account_id': 12000, 'date': '2015-07-31 00:06:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2

Personally, this is specifically for bug 1479138 so I would file a new bug Lakshmi and fix it in that commit so the defect and fix are properly tracked. I'd rather not be smuggling fixes for other things into patches"}, {'account_id': 10063, 'date': '2015-07-31 01:03:29.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I could go either way, but I see Ian's point.  Lakshmi says this bug existed already, so we can track separately. I didn't fully verify that, but I did go ahead and make a dependent patch linked to a new bug report and tested it out.

https://bugs.launchpad.net/searchlight/+bug/1480048
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/207719/

So, Lakshmi (or Ian or Steve) how about go ahead and +A this patch to get it in and check out the child patch.  I added you as co-author on the child patch, so Ian and Steve (or others will need to approve that one).  However, you can +1 it if you approve. commit_message:
Change Glance notifications to be create_or_update

The glance image plugin uses two separate functions for create and update based
on the notification type. Under these functions it is called update on the
elasticsearch client.  This call will fail with a 404 error if the image
doesn't already exist.  The reason for it not existing may be numerous
(Create notifications dropped due to some sort of error, user deletes from
index, etc), but we can not worry about why it may not exist.  Instead this
should do create_or_update like functionality and if the image doesn't exist
on the update call, it should be inserted.

This patch makes use of the elastic search functionality called doc_as_upsert,
which natively provides the type of handling desired as stated above.

Change-Id: Icd97e15ed549b644d6b1aa9d019a8dd0b44defe7
Closes-Bug: #1479138

commit_message:
VMware: store extra_specs object

Maintain the extra_specs object on the VI data structure. This
will enable us to configure the disk limits.

The is part of the blueprint vmware-limits

Change-Id: I837fec1a7ee77e4a260e0d68672b5495b6837285

commit_message:
VMware: Resource limits for memory

The flavor extra specs for quotas has been extended to support
 quota:memory_limit - The utilization of a virtual machine will
                      not exceed this limit, even if there are available
                      resources. This is typically used to ensure a
                      consistent performance of virtual machines
                      independent of available resources.
                      Units are MB.
 quota:memory_reservation -  guaranteed minimum reservation (MB)
 quota:memory_shares_level - the allocation level. This can be 'custom', 'high'
                             'normal' or 'low'.
 quota:memory_shares_share - in the event that 'custom' is used, this is the
                             number of shares.

Please see http://goo.gl/uepivS for an explanation of the above.

DocImpact

This is part of the blueprint vmware-limits

Change-Id: Idc77841768fae5f03cc88d6b6485b9c5056fe137

commit_message:
VMware: create common object for limits, reservations and shares

Currently we are supporting cpu limits, reservations and shares.
The same are also supported for disks, memory and vnics.

This patch creates a common data structure to be used to support all
of the above.

This is part of the blueprint vmware-limits

Change-Id: I0abf816a6e3b29f10f7380a5865d30e887c09766

commit_message:
VMware: add support for cores per socket

The VM config spec enables the caller to define the number of cores
per socket.

This is the number of cores among which to distribute CPUs in this
virtual machine.

The cores per socket can be configured per flavor extra specs via:
'hw:cpu_sockets' or specifically per image metadata via
'hw_cpu_sockets'.

DocImpact

Change-Id: I14df8e78969835ab28b579d61415c98c55a736f8

commit_message:
Add l3 service stub file

This change introduces the bare minimum of changes to make
routers and floating ip handling from an l3 service configurable,
*NOT* functional. It is just a stub file.

Partially Implements:
https://blueprints.launchpad.net/networking-midonet/+spec/midonet-ml2

Change-Id: I745b6c370adfcf5d0412879393f604bcce941e9e
Signed-off-by: Joe Mills <joe@midokura.com>

commit_message:
Disable lagency launch when LAUNCH_INSTANCE_LEGACY_ENABLED is False

The network topology page doesn't honor LAUNCH_INSTANCE_LEGACY_ENABLED,
even when LAUNCH_INSTANCE_LEGACY_ENABLED is set to false, the lagency
launch wizard is still shown.

Change-Id: I30167e28cee174da5b2cdfe41edff4e3f375d88e
Closes-bug: #1478710

commit_message:
Cache Keystone client instance

For large deployments Ironic drivers can generate many requests to
Keystone. But Keystone service catalog and auth token can be cached,
(they stored in the client instance).
This patch adds caching for Keystone client instance.

Change-Id: I8ad5a958afc858f8e2f150466615db382950a500

commit_message:
Allow ramdisk_id, kernel_id to be null on schema

Since is possible to create images with no
ramdisk_id, kernel_id parameters on glance v1,
then the schema-image.json needs to be modified to
allow null, string values for both attributes
and prevent LP #1447193 to happen with a glance v2
client.

APIImpact

Closes-Bug: #1447215
Related-Bug: #1447193

Change-Id: I645c797553ccaa84062f9ad28f2349ae738a0c96
Signed-off-by: Jorge Niedbalski <jorge.niedbalski@canonical.com>
(cherry picked from commit 82c63b1df4399db22dfd71e3326a6bfc1b372a9c)

commit_message:
Move hook-{name}-rtfd to proposal node

Our RTFD hook just does a curl request to upstream. As such, it is
very expensive to nodepool to build a node for the purpose of just
using curl.

Lets move the job to use the proposal node which is long living.

Change-Id: I8f407fdaeb890a4ae6a9b99caefe836b8f2f7819
Signed-off-by: Paul Belanger <pabelanger@redhat.com>

commit_message:
pass environment variables of proxy to tox

When a development environment is under a proxy, tox is failed even if
environment variables of the proxy are set.

This patch fix this problem.

Change-Id: I09ba728fd457b96589dd9246e55fb311f677b3dc

commit_message:
Add APIs for deleting logical router port

Add APIs to delete logical router port.  Also adjust
the add logical port API since the OVN_Northbound schema
now supports the 'name' field.

Change-Id: I34a3a796c4608debf9da279435047af480d02ee0

commit_message:
distributed coordinated notifications

this patch enables a queue per pipeline per agent. each agent can
send data to pipeline queue set of any agent but only listens to it's
own pipeline queue. when receiving a notification, the agent will:
1. build datapoint
2. calculate hash key based on (hardcoded) attribute and mod hash
   by number of active agents
3. sends the data to single agents pipeline queue set.

ex. two agents, sample1 with res_id=1 and sample2 with res_id=2
1. agent1 builds both samples
2. hash(sample1) % 2 (num agents) == agent1 sends sample to agent2
   pipeline queue.
2a. agent2 process sample1
3. hash(sample2) % 2 (num agents) == agent1 sends sample to agent1
   pipeline queue.
3a. agent1 process sample2

Implements blueprint distributed-coordinated-notifications

Change-Id: Iab52cae0a5bfbc747a2918e67dfe8da5fd0fda84

[{'account_id': 8376, 'date': '2015-07-17 07:04:20.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 10068, 'date': '2015-07-17 07:04:28.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC
    Workflow: http://docs.openstack.org/infra/manual/developers.html

commit_message:
swiftclient: add short options to help message

- add usage strings for short option such as '-a' for '--all'
  This add all short options  to usage text.
- add missing --header usage help for download command
- some cometic changes

Closes-bug: #1475511

Change-Id: Ibfecac8764669540fa025787548133a50fa50b10
Signed-off-by: Hiroshi Miura <miurahr@nttdata.co.jp>

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 1179, 'date': '2015-07-29 16:20:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Wow!  Nice work Carlos, I can see you've already got a bunch of feedback - must have struck a nerve.

FWIW, I've found with something as extremely *difficult* as technical writing, using an imprecise and subjective tool like English language - it can be *really* hard to get a set of words that everyone thinks is optimal.  Most doc changes in swift are merged by shear attrition - once everyone is exhausted it becomes easier to remember that "now is often better than never".  IME, the easiest way to get every one tired out is to encourage them to "yes, please, much better, thank you for the feedback - please just push that over this change, thank you!"

It's actually possible for any person who has a gerrit change checked out to make fixes and then type `git review` and replace the latest patch set here with another version that includes their suggestions - no change in authorship.  Nonetheless, people are reserved about "fixing" your work unless you actively encourage them to participate collaboratively by doing.

But I think you can see from the comments here, most suggestions are fixes that are obviously better - you just missed it, or didn't think about it.  The rest you'll probably have zero-preference on either way.

Good Luck!'}, {'account_id': 597, 'date': '2015-07-29 17:00:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

commit_message:
Swift documentation for first-time contributors.

In this change, there are proposed improvement to Swift documentation aimed at
first-time contributors. They include a simplification of the Getting
Started page and a new page with some basic instructions/commands that the
first-time contributor should know. In addition, it shows some common errors
that the first-time contributor may find when executing git rebase and
information on how to track your changes.

Change-Id: I704202955093736b2f3b4102a649690a0392c6b0

It's a pretty well known fact in the networking world that the ordering of DNS nameservers matter. However, in Neutron, the ordering of the dns nameservers in a subnet-create or subnet-update API command is not maintained. The proper solution is to make sure that the order is maintained when we persist the list to the DB, and when we send that list via RPC to the DHCP agent. This is par preferable to adding a configuration value that indicates the "major" server.'}, {'account_id': 8873, 'date': '2015-07-08 14:52:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Please see:
https://bugs.launchpad.net/neutron/+bug/1218629'}, {'account_id': 11682, 'date': '2015-07-08 14:56:45.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1
