The problem is that the order of the DNS servers from the subnet create/update call is not maintained.  That is what needs to be fixed.  Adding logic for a new field "primary_dns_nameserver" feels like a hack since it does not fix the root issue.'}, {'account_id': 14562, 'date': '2015-07-11 08:27:53.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

Thanks for John's reply. This patch is not point the order of DNS servers.   It is just point a primary DNS server. Because the max count of DNS servers is three in configure file of DNS server(/etc/resolv.conf)."}, {'account_id': 11682, 'date': '2015-07-11 13:55:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

As has been said previously, adding a parameter to the model instead of just persisting order in the DB and RPC is the wrong way to solve the problem.'}, {'account_id': 14562, 'date': '2015-07-12 06:41:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Thx for your reply. Could you tell me a better way to solve this problem?'}, {'account_id': 14562, 'date': '2015-07-12 12:47:22.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

Hi, all. I try to record the order of DNS nameservers when create/update subnet's nameservers one by one. The order of stored data in DB is same when I create/update a subnet with DNS nameservers '1.1.1.1' '2.2.2.2' or nameservers '2.2.2.2' '1.1.1.1'. It seems that sqlalchemy sorted data when put data into DB."}, {'account_id': 8873, 'date': '2015-07-12 20:57:32.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

Keep in mind that when you update a subnet the dns_nameservers are put in a set which does not retain order (_update_subnet_dns_nameservers in neutron/db/ipam_backend/mixin). I don't see the same problem when a subnet is created. The agent seems to retain ordering from whatever it got in the RPC message. As for the RPC layer, the DHCP RPC handler just issues core_plugin.get_subnets(). Apart from the first issue with the set container and update_subnet, the only issue left is verifying that SQLAlchemy and the different backends don't mess up ordering when you add DB objects in to a session and later retrieve them via a relationship/join. If that is found to be an issue we can look into serializing the DNS records differently, and I'm sure there's plenty of other solutions."}, {'account_id': 8873, 'date': '2015-07-12 21:00:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

Reading your previous comment I see that something in the DB layer is sorting the DNS records by the address (Which is the primary key). We can look in to persisting the entire list of DNS records in a single row in the DB, or if we want to retain the data normalized you'll have to spend some time looking in to alternative solutions, like adding an ordering column."}, {'account_id': 14562, 'date': '2015-07-13 14:06:25.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 14562, 'date': '2015-07-13 14:10:30.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 6.'}, {'account_id': 14562, 'date': '2015-07-13 14:11:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-07-08 14:31:48.000000000', 'message': 'Add dns server prioritization for subnet

Currently, there is no dns servers prioritization for subnets
for Neutron. Generally speaking, it is useful that dns servers
has prioritization.

Change option "dns-server" in dnsmasq process when update a subnet's
dns nameserver. By doing this, it is can change dns server prioritization
for subnet.

Change-Id: Id937aea411397d39370368a4eb45be26c4eefa9e
'}, {'created': '2015-07-10 07:04:02.000000000', 'message': "Add dns server prioritization for subnet

Currently, there is no dns servers prioritization for subnets
for Neutron. Generally speaking, it is useful that dns servers
has prioritization.

Add new attribute named 'major_dns_nameserver' to subnet.
So we can point a major dns nameserver when create a subnet which
has dns nameserver. We can also update major dnsnameserver if
the major dns nameserver in old dns nameservers.

Change-Id: Id937aea411397d39370368a4eb45be26c4eefa9e
"}, {'created': '2015-07-11 01:05:21.000000000', 'message': 'Add dns server prioritization for subnet

Currently, there is no dns servers prioritization for subnets
for Neutron. Generally speaking, it is useful that dns servers
has prioritization.

Add new attribute named 'primary_dns_nameserver' to subnet.
So we can primary a major dns nameserver when create a subnet which
has dns nameserver. We can also update major dnsnameserver if
the primary dns nameserver in old dns nameservers.

VM get IP address and get dns info from dnsmasq process, and dnsmasq
has a file named opts which include DNS infos. Just like this:
"dns-server,1.2.3.4,8.8.8.8,114.114.114.114". If we want to change
DNS prioritization we need to change the IP address's order. VM's
resolv.conf will change nameserver orders after we do this.

Close-Bug: https://bugs.launchpad.net/neutron/+bug/1218629
Change-Id: Id937aea411397d39370368a4eb45be26c4eefa9e

commit_message:
Keep dns nameserver order consistency

Currently, there is no dns servers prioritization for subnets
for Neutron.

Generally speaking, it is useful to keep the order of dns
nameservers consistent. Add a new column named 'order' in table
'dnsnameservers' and add nameserver into DB one by one.

Closes-Bug: #1218629
Implements: blueprint keep-dns-nameserver-orderconsistency
Change-Id: Id937aea411397d39370368a4eb45be26c4eefa9e

commit_message:
Replace nosetests with pytest

Now we use pytests in fuel-web and nosetests in python-fuelclient, so it's
better to choose one of them and pytest more preferable choice. Same framework
for stackforge python projects gives us more unified ecosystem for testing and
also it's easier to support only one.

Closes-Bug: #1471815
Change-Id: I786bc966572a3e022592a40a3b61596a6c264e54

commit_message:
SSH Storage
In order to give flexibility Freezer needs to be able
to store data to a remote file system host using ssh/scp
instead instead of Swift.

Change-Id: Ia6a790e3e3b6bb9e4e36d457ba0b72c114f8a895
Implements: blueprint ssh-media

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-07-30 12:47:21.000000000', 'message': "remove conntrackd package

As per bug discussion, conntrackd is actually not needed for netfilter
framework, and given that users do not appear to find the logs useful
(the only reason we're using conntrackd), let's just remove it.

This commit also defines a variable container_remove_packages so that
the list of packages to remove from containers can be added to in the
future.

NOTE: removing conntrackd does not unload the kernel conntrack modules
or disable the netfilter conntrack framework. It simply means we are not
gathering ostensibly useless logging. The kernel conntrack flows can
still be interrogated with the 'conntrack' userspace cli tool, for real
time debugging.

Change-Id: Ic74e65a6fe27060dc94bfc2f250cd53fb153c7c8
Closes-Bug: 1457196

commit_message:
remove conntrackd package

As per bug discussion, conntrackd is actually not needed for netfilter
framework, and given that users do not appear to find the logs useful
(the only reason we're using conntrackd), let's just remove it.

This commit also defines a variable container_remove_packages so that
the list of packages to remove from containers can be added to in the
future.

NOTE: removing conntrackd does not unload the kernel conntrack modules
or disable the netfilter conntrack framework. It simply means we are not
gathering ostensibly useless logging. The kernel conntrack flows can
still be interrogated with the 'conntrack' userspace cli tool, for real
time debugging.

Change-Id: Ic74e65a6fe27060dc94bfc2f250cd53fb153c7c8
Closes-Bug: 1457196
(cherry picked from commit 0da48344c6bdff988473da1aa7e9e0f6ef724680)

commit_message:
Configure incorrect cron file name

OpenStack install OpenSUSE 13.2 indicates incorrect cron file name.
Cron file name is below change.

Original:
/etc/cron.hourly/keystone

Changed:
/etc/cron.hourly/openstack-keystone.

Source File: /doc/install-guide/section_keystone-install.xml

Change-Id: I6f27b0f67038b0446adae8f791416b72269a9978
Closes-Bug: #1475703

commit_message:
Warn user about unsupported content type

Raise exception to user when the specified content type is unsupported, instead
of sliently replacing it to default type 'application/json'.

Change-Id: I57dac2dca743d128fbc27dfb4c836885f69e3fae
Closes-Bug: #1480036

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

commit_message:
[WIP] [install-guide] remove unnecessary syntax highlighting

There are a lot of programlistings using syntax highlighting where it
does not makes sense, resulting in a lot of wrong, incosistent, and/or
incomplete highlights in the generated programlistings.

Change-Id: I9781ce2218d3fd8bd9c9f55d54a9c5cdd66ec71d

[{'created': '2015-07-28 18:46:26.000000000', 'message': "Fix slow unit tests

As of liberty.2, the Manila unit tests are taking ~60 seconds to run
on my system. A dozen or so of the tests consistently take an integral
number of seconds to run (i.e. 1, 2, 3 or 4 seconds), indicating the
presence of a time.sleep() call in the code that hasn't been mocked.
By mocking time.sleep() and time.time() in just a few files, the time
needed to run the unit tests falls by a third to ~40 seconds (!).

Change-Id: I66a6d864823b10a4193eadf65a1c5d3028f2afa7
Closes-bug: 1478644
"}]
commit_message:
Fix slow unit tests

As of liberty.2, the Manila unit tests are taking ~60 seconds to run
on my system. A dozen or so of the tests consistently take an integral
number of seconds to run (i.e. 1, 2, 3 or 4 seconds), indicating the
presence of a time.sleep() call in the code that hasn't been mocked.
By mocking time.sleep() and time.time() in just a few files, the time
needed to run the unit tests falls by a third to ~40 seconds (!).

Change-Id: I66a6d864823b10a4193eadf65a1c5d3028f2afa7
Closes-bug: 1478644

commit_message:
Keep alarm other attrs constantly after evaluating an alarm

When evaluating a threshold alarm, the alarm rule of the *alarm* object
will be changed, because in the _statistics() method, the
alarm.rule['query'] is referenced and extended. When the alarm being
refreshed, the *alarm* object will be updated to db in _refresh()
method, that will cause the alarm's query definition being extended
repeatedly.

Change-Id: Iefb4646ee9d07a272550f13a91ae60220032e4db

commit_message:
MongoDB cluster strategy missing create_admin_user

The strategy's guestagent does not have a cast for the create_admin_user
command. This is needed during cluster create.

Change-Id: Ied11fd0cc9b031b7f671ea8f92463e353b7fc360
Closes-bug: #1476355

If job_status changed during iteration, _clean queried on keys no longer in the dictionary
See https://bugs.launchpad.net/monasca/+bug/1476313
This does not fix this bug, it only mitigates one of the symptoms.
I am not sure that items() is thread safe, but it does reduce the window of time during which problems can occur
  by collecting all values upfront.

Change-Id: Ibe206f45ff308a8b6d04eda28367846105414491
'}]
commit_message:
Mitigates job_status dict change during iteration

If job_status changed during iteration, _clean queried on keys no longer in the dictionary
See https://bugs.launchpad.net/monasca/+bug/1476313
This does not fix this bug, it only mitigates one of the symptoms.
I am not sure that items() is thread safe, but it does reduce the window of time during which problems can occur
  by collecting all values upfront.

Change-Id: Ibe206f45ff308a8b6d04eda28367846105414491

openstack --os-auth-url http://openstack-controller:35357 --os-project-name admin --os-username admin --os-auth-type password project list

fails with following error

ERROR: openstack The resource could not be found. (HTTP 404)

bu by changing OS_AUTH_URL, it works
openstack --os-auth-url http://openstack-controller:35357/v2.0 --os-project-name admin --os-username admin --os-auth-type password project list

Change-Id: I084b83f868aa5ee273a81bdb66bc1b52ae4a7037
Closes-Bug: #1451114
'}]
commit_message:
Change incorrect syntax in installation guide

Built: 2015-05-02T13:34:49 00:00
git SHA: 84fad0c54b1ff7f3401adfe3aee4d34158b50d33
URL: http://docs.openstack.org/kilo/install-guide/install/apt/content/keystone-verify.html
source File: file:/home/jenkins/workspace/openstack-manuals-tox-doc-publishdocs/doc/install-guide/section_keystone-verify.xml
xml:id: keystone-verify

openstack --os-auth-url http://openstack-controller:35357 --os-project-name admin --os-username admin --os-auth-type password project list

fails with following error

ERROR: openstack The resource could not be found. (HTTP 404)

bu by changing OS_AUTH_URL, it works
openstack --os-auth-url http://openstack-controller:35357/v2.0 --os-project-name admin --os-username admin --os-auth-type password project list

Change-Id: I084b83f868aa5ee273a81bdb66bc1b52ae4a7037
Closes-Bug: #1451114

commit_message:
libvirt: simplify logic of checking PCI device's existence

Current logic of detecting a PCI device is a little complicated.
Let's switch to use Xpath simplify this.

Partial-Bug: #1407915

Change-Id: I5e4419b6e5461a62d85d192b7b9c7b5d8d853b71

commit_message:
Use oslo.log instead of oslo-incubator logging

log module has been removed from oslo-incubator after oslo.log was
released.

Change-Id: I1cb764c6bd978be71c5a9a6dd26d53ebea5192bb
Implements: blueprint port-oslo-incubator-to-oslo-log

commit_message:
Use oslo.log instead of oslo-incubator logging

log module has been removed from oslo-incubator after oslo.log was
released. This change will fail tests till a new guest image is built
with oslo.log in the requirements.txt file. The change
https://review.openstack.org/162676 has been submitted to get a new
guest image.

Implements: blueprint port-oslo-incubator-to-oslo-log
Depends-On: I1cb764c6bd978be71c5a9a6dd26d53ebea5192bb
Change-Id: I753573c14facf5bf916d6deee8c1cd7f112a9f48

commit_message:
Sync oslo-incubator

This should be the final sync of oslo-incubator pre-Kilo. Detailed
changelist follows.

_i18n.py

ba544bbc switch to oslo_i18n

eventlet_backdoor.py

7cc15017 Change oslo.config to oslo_config
875eb30d Remove oslo.log code and clean up versionutils API
c6863a5c Remove unnecessary import of eventlet

loopingcall.py

875eb30d Remove oslo.log code and clean up versionutils API

periodic_task.py

7cc15017 Change oslo.config to oslo_config
875eb30d Remove oslo.log code and clean up versionutils API
c9166a2f Allow overriding name for periodic tasks
4abeda60 Separate add_periodic_task from the metaclass __init__

service.py

4dcc8b35 Optimization of waiting subprocesses in ProcessLauncher
7cc15017 Change oslo.config to oslo_config
875eb30d Remove oslo.log code and clean up versionutils API
b888c0fa Merge "Added graceful argument on Service.stop method"
492fa4a3 Added graceful argument on Service.stop method
7ec3fab2 Remove extra white space in log message

systemd.py

875eb30d Remove oslo.log code and clean up versionutils API

threadgroup.py

875eb30d Remove oslo.log code and clean up versionutils API

versionutils.py

154263ae Add liberty release name to versionutils
fc6f2479 Switch from oslo.config to oslo_config
875eb30d Remove oslo.log code and clean up versionutils API

Other changes are to address the fact that periodic_task no longer
supports the ticks_between_runs argument.

Change-Id: Idf7899ead53c14c32dc343f2249f105e4b053209

Currently we don't get generated parent dir indexes for swift uploaded
logs. This is mostly ok for check/gate jobs as we address the log dirs
directly in the path supplied to gerrit and presented to users. For post
jobs we do not do this so rely on something to provide a proper index.
Go back to apache uploaded logs in addition to swift uploaded logs so
that these files will be indexed until we can set up indexing with
swift.

Change-Id: I7f688834e0d3ad91b81dcbde7643a4b5c208748e
"}]
commit_message:
Write post job logs to apache and swift

Currently we don't get generated parent dir indexes for swift uploaded
logs. This is mostly ok for check/gate jobs as we address the log dirs
directly in the path supplied to gerrit and presented to users. For post
jobs we do not do this so rely on something to provide a proper index.
Go back to apache uploaded logs in addition to swift uploaded logs so
that these files will be indexed until we can set up indexing with
swift.

Change-Id: I7f688834e0d3ad91b81dcbde7643a4b5c208748e

commit_message:
Create a repository for stackforge/xstatic-roboto-fontface

Roboto is the font for Google's Material Design.

We plan on using this in Horizon to provide a theme that
implements Google's Material Design.  This patch creates
a repo for it.

commit_message:
Rakefile: create a task to copy logs

When running beaker with Jenkins, it's useful to get the logs at the end
of the job, so we can easily debug eventual failures.

This patch aims to create a Rake task to copy the logs. For that, we
need to make sure WORKSPACE is set (automatically done when running the
job on a Jenkins node). This task will copy the Keystone logs in the workspace.

To run the task, you need to run `rake copy_logs` which is what
OpenStack Infra is doing.

Change-Id: I54550cbce7eb1eb0189e29481649aeb2525c8130

I wonder if it is better not to deduct the volume_gb from free_capacity_gb in consume_from_volume in host_manager for thin provisioning. If so, we don't need to call publish_service_capabilities after create volume is complete.

Winston, what do you think?"}, {'account_id': 2759, 'date': '2015-07-23 03:07:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Code-Review-1

ChenYing, bug 1475475 was marked as duplicate of bug 1445398, please change bug # in your commit message.

Xing, below is my comment on bug 1445398:

"Now you want to be smarter about thin provisioning, but please don't assume a volume is thin provisioned when backend supports thin provision. Because there are the cases where a backend supports both thin and thick and cinder doesn't know the provision for the volume. Even ideally, Cinder knows a volume is thin provisioned, is it safe to not deduct free_capacity_gb for the backend? Consider this case: a volume is thin provisioned

    -------------+----+-----+------------+---------------------------------------------------+
                     ^ ^
        vol_stats_update (60s interval) vol_stats_update
                             ^
                          vol created (thin)
                                      ^
                                   vol attached
                                                       ^
                                                  vol being written data

Is it safe to deduct nothing for a thin-provisioned volume from free before next vol_stats_update is available? It's only safe if that volume is not in-use.

 Assuming a volume being thick is simple, and it works. It might be too strict for some edge cases when the capacity of the backend is near the limit. But like I said earlier, it is safer to being conservative. Not allowing a few new volume to be created within short period of time vs. backend reach certain limit become readonly, you can pick."

Now if we do update service capabilities on every success volume create, I share the same concern on load it may generate to a busy system.

I kept saying this is a edge case, and it's not a bug to be conservative AND SAFE.'}, {'account_id': 2759, 'date': '2015-07-23 03:09:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

Grr, the format of my previous comment is totally messed up.  Hopefully you can still get what I am trying to say.'}, {'account_id': 6491, 'date': '2015-07-23 03:24:40.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

Hi Winston,

Yes, I got what you are saying. Sure, let's be conservative. Thanks."}, {'account_id': 6491, 'date': '2015-07-23 03:34:04.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5: Code-Review-1

Please update the commit message based on Winston's suggestion. commit_message:
Publish capabilities after volume creation successful

Create several thin provisioned volumes within one minute,
if one volume size is larger than host's free_capacity_gb and
smaller than free_virtual, this creation will be successful,
but the next volume creation will be failed. Publishing service
capabilities after volume creation successful, this bug will
be fixed.

Change-Id: Id3e195d414056c6baeb2afc263d52c7af6290749
Closes-Bug: #1445398

commit_message:
Adds parameter specification for #call()

Adds 1st parameter specification to #call method so that
 1) $dict(key) will not lead to attempt to call dict
 2) it would be possible to implement custom #call versions
     (for example to make $dict(key) possible)

Change-Id: I10eb17b6fa2718b90beceecc84e2ccb2e7eb420d

commit_message:
Fixes bug with positional arg specs

When function has *args parameter it is always the last positional
argument. In yaql it is possible to declare parameters by their
position rather than by the name. But for *args position number
it didn't worked as expected

commit_message:
Create a repository for stackforge/xstatic-mdi

MDI provides Google's Material Design Icons in SCSS format
We plan on using this in Horizon to provide a theme that
implements Google's Material Design.  This patch creates
a repo for it.

Change-Id: Icab5c5c20b60d95d0ed6ba089558c9dea0051e9f

commit_message:
add E006: check for lines longer than 79 columns

This mimics the widely accepted convention from PEP8 and many other
places that lines longer than 79 columns can not only cause problems
when reading/writing code, but also often indicate a bad smell,
e.g. too many levels of indentation due to overly complex functions
which require refactoring into smaller chunks.

Change-Id: Ic2532676e46e93f129d590d1fa7a044ef65f50fb

commit_message:
Add constraint of IntegerType maximum for API

Currently, the Ceilometer API has no constraint of maximum of int
type. That will cause error when a python unlimited int num
converted to C int type(as the bug described).

This change adds constraint of IntegerType maximum for API, including
period and evaluation_periods fields of alarm threshold_rule, and
search_offset query field.

Change-Id: If9afa1ce8ef31f45e80ef19b26e199c69b5ec26e
Closes-bug: #1315819
DocImpact

[{'created': '2015-07-27 16:30:29.000000000', 'message': 'Fix Keystone Auth and Tests

Keystone Auth was previously non-functional as the Keystone
API resource being used does not support Roles as required
by the function to map to Anchor Groups.

This was further compounded by the required HTTP return code
being 200 (OK), but the function with POST returns a 201
(CREATED).

This change, switches to to using a GET Keystone API
resource to validate the token passed in by the user.

The keystone unit tests have been updated to a real sample
JSON response from the resource called (rather than the
bogus one previously used) and split up the 3 current tests
into separate functions.

However, long term I really think we will want to switch to
using keystonemiddleware library - rather than our homebrew
usage.

Change-Id: I7b8d81764934638040120bcefe81d012748007c8
Closes-Bug: #1478532
Signed-off-by: Dave Walker (Daviey) <email@daviey.com>
'}]
commit_message:
Fix Keystone Auth and Tests

Keystone Auth was previously non-functional as the Keystone
API resource being used does not support Roles as required
by the function to map to Anchor Groups.

This was further compounded by the required HTTP return code
being 200 (OK), but the function with POST returns a 201
(CREATED).

This change, switches to to using a GET Keystone API
resource to validate the token passed in by the user.

The keystone unit tests have been updated to a real sample
JSON response from the resource called (rather than the
bogus one previously used) and split up the 3 current tests
into separate functions.

However, long term I really think we will want to switch to
using keystonemiddleware library - rather than our homebrew
usage.

Change-Id: I7b8d81764934638040120bcefe81d012748007c8
Closes-Bug: #1478532
Signed-off-by: Dave Walker (Daviey) <email@daviey.com>

commit_message:
Do not run keystone-propose-config-updates

There's no genconfig target in juno and kilo, do not run the job there.

Change-Id: I0488c707efc8b4283df51b1bb6cd06b3a05f3931

Python 3: fix test_attributes

In Python 3, strings have an __iter__ method, which makes convert_to_list fail.

commit_message:
Add ability for GET path to see/select alternate frag archs

Changes include:
- storage nodes reporting when they have >1 fragment archive
available
- GET path recognizing alternates, when to use them and building
up the getters accordingly
- GET path assuring that even if it has enough FA's that they
all come from the same set (via etag) and if not try GETs from
the parity nodes to see if they have some more.  This addresses
the case where a simple overwrite PUT happens with a node off
and a subsequent GET comes in while its back but before it gets
updated with the latest stuff.
- associated test changes for existing code
- new unit tests and new probe tests

Co-Authored-By: Clay Gerrard <clay.gerrard@gmail.com>
Closes-Bug: 1457691
Change-Id: I2491edaa56dcf4eb9e864bbf263be8fa588d64c2

[{'account_id': 15862, 'date': '2015-07-16 19:07:59.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 15862, 'date': '2015-07-16 19:22:34.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 11655, 'date': '2015-07-16 19:39:46.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

I can see the argument to make the retries configurable based on the environment, as everyone's hardware is different, but each environment is going to have different risks, and I am concerned changing the logic to always retry on any failure that is not a core dump might cause other deployments more problems than it would prevent, especially if the error is a transient error.  In the case where the previous retry logic was added, it was a case of the BMC bridge was too busy to pass along the command because Ironic was ultimately flooding it with traffic as it was serving a substantial number of cartridges.  By chance is this a similar case?"}, {'account_id': 15862, 'date': '2015-07-16 19:56:55.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

So far we encountered 2 kinds of ipmi issues:
1. ipmitool: lanplus.c:2153: ipmi_lanplus_send_payload: Assertion `session->v2_data.session_state == LANPLUS_STATE_PRESESSION' failed.

2. Error: Unable to establish IPMI v2 / RMCP+ session\r\nUnable to send RAW command (channel=0x0 netfn=0x0 lun=0x0 cmd=0x8)

Both are retriable. 

Also, for some of our servers, BMC will temporarily go down if the servers are rebooted.

Retry throttling is already in place, I don't think this will worsen the situation."}, {'account_id': 15862, 'date': '2015-07-16 20:02:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

We have various models of servers in data centers, each model has different ipmi behaviors. 
Our home-brew baremetal solution does all the kinds of reties, even bmc reset, such measures did improve the reliability.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-07-16 20:24:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

I'm still more inclined to be on the cautious side of things and only configure for what we know can be retried but I think this would be a good topic of discussion in IRC."}, {'account_id': 11655, 'date': '2015-07-20 12:14:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

For what its worth, you may want to try and fix the pep8 and unit test failures.'}, {'account_id': 6773, 'date': '2015-07-21 13:12:05.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

Hi jxiaobin,

Thanks for the patch I think I agree with @Julia here, I don't think it's a good thing to expose in a configuration variable this sort of behavior. As you said things behave differently on different servers so setting it globally on the configuration file doesn't seem to be a good idea.

FWIW I have seem a lot of the error 1) you pointed out and for me it was never retry-able[1]. The workaround to fix those is by resetting the BMC, so I agree with you that it would be good to have some APIs in Ironic to do such actions.

[1] ipmitool: lanplus.c:2177: ipmi_lanplus_send_payload: Assertion `session->v2_data.session_state == LANPLUS_STATE_PRESESSION' failed.
Aborted (core dumped)"}, {'account_id': 15862, 'date': '2015-07-30 22:39:49.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I don't want to say that, but I really feel ironic is a project exclusively for HP & Rackspace use cases."}, {'account_id': 15862, 'date': '2015-07-30 22:40:00.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]

commit_message:
Retry ipmi commands unless the failure is not retriable

Consider that image deployment is a time-consuming operation, most
ipmi failures worth retrying, even when BMC is temporarily offline.
List keywords of error messages in configuration file, ipmi command
will be retried if runtime error message does not match keywords.

Change-Id: I444ec23a40bc044117699315c4d3257414a9d85b
Closes-Bug: 1474953

commit_message:
libvirt: Remove error messages from multipath command output before parsing

Changes the implementation of _get_multipath_device_name() to use
linuxscsi.find_multipath_device().
This fixes an issue in _get_multipath_device_name() that fails to
parse the output from 'multipath' command when the stdout contains
error messages in addition to the expected output.

Change-Id: I7af5c8c8c351e7921881cb3ece4e61280dc9a9b8
Closes-Bug: #1433204

commit_message:
Only run constraints proposal for master

At the moment we're disinterested in constraints proposals to the
stable/kilo branch, so drop propose-requirements-constraints-kilo
for now. It's easy to add back later when we want.

Change-Id: I97e40b9958cba7d459db42ca85b3ec650126ff15

Why is this in stackforge and not in openstack?

Do you plan to move this at one point to the openstack namespace?

Please also explain a bit better what this repo is needed for. Do you have any references to other pages that share some light on what you plan to do?

Note that you created voting jobs, your very first patch needs to add all the infrastructure so that these job pass.'}, {'account_id': 10035, 'date': '2015-07-19 00:03:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 13786, 'date': '2015-07-20 20:59:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Why is this in stackforge and not in openstack?
[Yichen] I was thought StackForge is the place for OpenStack *related* projects, and I've did the same to VMTP tool. Both tools are for data plane performance and scale testing tools, and shouldn't it be in StackForge?

Do you plan to move this at one point to the openstack namespace?
[Yichen] I have no idea whether this kind of tool should be in StackForge or OpenStack. Probably you can give me some guidance about which to pick, and I am OK with either of them.

Please also explain a bit better what this repo is needed for. Do you have any references to other pages that share some light on what you plan to do?
[Yichen] Yes, we have some documents already including blueprint, how-to pages, but they are WIP, and not really good enough to become public. 
[Yichen] Here is a snip which explains what this is, hope that answers your question:
KloudBuster is a new open source tool that allows anybody - even with little OpenStack experience - to load any Neutron OpenStack cloud at massive data plane scale swiftly and effortlessly, and comes "all batteries included" without the need for expensive test equipment. KloudBuster is capable of staging and generating any amount of HTTP traffic involving real HTTP servers and simulated HTTP users, and providing synthesized results in the form of easy to understand charts that characterize the behavior of the OpenStack data plane under load.

Note that you created voting jobs, your very first patch needs to add all the infrastructure so that these job pass.
[Yichen] Yes. I have those things in plan, and will make sure all voting jobs are pssing!'}, {'account_id': 11744, 'date': '2015-07-20 21:11:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

To answer to Andreas, it looks like new openstack services would first start in stackforge then later migrate to openstack if there is any interest. So it looks like stackforge is more appropriate than openstack for kloudbuster.
That code has been in development internally at Cisco for ~5 months and is being used for scale testing. It is being pushed out to stackforge to benefit the community (mostly scale testing and devops) and by external openstack users requests.
It might be presented at the Tokyo summit if the presentation is selected (hence we really need it in stackforge to be ready for Tokyo).'}, {'account_id': 6547, 'date': '2015-07-22 13:32:24.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

Alec, moving repos from stackforge to openstack is *expensive*. We'd rather have projects start directly in openstack which is possible as part of the big tent. Either as a separate team or as a repo under an existing team.

See also this review: https://review.openstack.org/192016"}, {'account_id': 13786, 'date': '2015-07-22 18:50:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

To Andreas:
So you are suggesting to create the project in OpenStack directly, right? I will go ahead and do that.

Just a quick question before abandon this review, probably all I need is to change from stackforge to openstack, right? Is there any additional things that I need to do, or you happen to have some other documents that I can refer to?'}, {'account_id': 6547, 'date': '2015-07-22 18:56:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

I suggest you discuss this with some TC members first, check the review I mentioned and also http://docs.openstack.org/infra/manual/creators.html'}, {'account_id': 11744, 'date': '2015-07-25 00:51:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: -Code-Review

Looks like stackforge is being deprecated and new projects should be hosted under openstack directly.
Thanks for pointing this out Andreas.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-07-30 21:16:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Verified-1

Merge Failed.

This change or one of its cross-repo dependencies was unable to be automatically merged with the current state of its repository. Please rebase the change and upload a new patchset.'}, {'account_id': 13786, 'date': '2015-07-30 21:46:41.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]

commit_message:
Add DiskNotFound and VolumeNotFound test

Add DiskNotFound and VolumeNotFound exception test cases for
shutdown action of instance, to make sure we catch them
and only log the exception.

Change-Id: I204fb2f1850f8bce2be27cb4c65cec0a0e95ea33

commit_message:
Adds os_admin_user to common OS image prop metadef

This will add os_admin_user to the list of common properties for
operating systems metadata definition.

Commit I215bb82668df074141397909b58fa9189f46b4da is adding
os_admin_user to the list of image metadata it understands.  As
a result, it's beneficial to also have that property defined
in the metadef.

Change-Id: I7cf70acf3c6a4f801b34d52926c444d05b79fd51
Implements: blueprint libvirt-set-admin-password

[{'created': '2015-07-16 09:42:33.000000000', 'message': '[WIP] BGP Dynamic Routing: adding agent and scheduling

Dynamic routing needs a new agent that will host the BGP speaker driver
and will do the actual communication between BGP peers.
This agent will take information from a single BGP speaker entity,
that has all the information that the agent needs to do the routing
exchange: peers and routes. In this approach, an agent can only host one
BGP speaker to avoid conflicts.
This commit intruduces a dummy agent that auto-registers to Neutron API
and send keep-alive messages.

A binding between the agent and the BGP speaker is mandatory in the
database and also the api endpoints to let the user
associate/disassociate a BGP speaker to an agent.
There is also an autoscheduling feature that will assign a BGP speaker
to the first agent that asks for synchronization. Default
scheduler class will only assign non-assigned BGP speakers to
agents.

HA feature (two agents hosting the same routing instance) has to be done manually.

commit_message:
[WIP] BGP Dynamic Routing: adding agent and scheduling

Dynamic routing needs a new agent that will host the BGP speaker driver
and will do the actual communication between BGP peers.
This agent will take information from a single BGP speaker entity,
that has all the information that the agent needs to do the routing
exchange: peers and routes. In this approach, an agent can only host one
BGP speaker to avoid conflicts.
This commit intruduces a dummy agent that auto-registers to Neutron API
and send keep-alive messages.

A binding between the agent and the BGP speaker is mandatory in the
database and also the api endpoints to let the user
associate/disassociate a BGP speaker to an agent.
There is also an autoscheduling feature that will assign a BGP speaker
to the first agent that asks for synchronization. Default
scheduler class will only assign non-assigned BGP speakers to
agents.

HA feature (two agents hosting the same routing instance) has to be done manually.

Outstanding Items:
- Unit and API testcases
- RpcCallback implementation

Change-Id: Ib5ea27c477c0187cd81ea5f5307c83b712c003ff
Partially-Implements: blueprint bgp-dynamic-routing
Co-Authored-By: Ryan Tidwell <ryan.tidwell@hp.com>
Co-Authored-By: Jaume Devesa <devvesa@gmail.com>

commit_message:
[config-reference] barbican config options missing

The config reference guide in the block storage section is
missing info to allow the barbican key manager to be configured
to support the volume encryption feature.

Change-Id: I127296ca018ab04a7f85129b3c2304e8a2b5a588
Closes-Bug: #1474028

Synchronized RPM spec with Python requiremensts

Since Python requirements were changed several times
there is a need to update RPM spec to match both
requirements.txt and Mirantis mirror.

Closes-bug: #1477127

commit_message:
Delegate failure capturing to a object that is returned on run

This allows capturing of tracebacks and using the full logging
support when a non-process-pool executor is being used which makes
the handling of exceptions and there logging more natural (vs
just printing the traceback).

Change-Id: I40e7841f57209964f01a43a581504a309906b475

It seems like either the dictionary should be an attribute of the machine itself (and used in the logs) or the this should have an option to include the name that will be in the logs in the output produced here.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-07-06 20:44:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified-1

Ah, good question, soooo the other idea for doing this was to have the following be used.

Instead of:
 
  def add_state(self, state):
    self.add_labeled_state(state, str(state))

We would add this:

  def add_labeled_state(self, state, label):
     ...

  def get_label(self, state):
     ...

Then the label can be used elsewhere (the label being something that can be its string name, which can then also be used in this converter thing, instead of needing a dict to do the conversions). It can also be passed to logs or other as desired (if people associate a callback that can use that information)...

Thoughts?'}, {'account_id': 1297, 'date': '2015-07-06 21:33:05.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

As for logs of machine itself, what logs do u mean? 

Machines don't afaik have any logs, but people can associate transition callbacks that can produce logs (or do other things).

This is similar to what ironic/taskflow/others(?) are doing with something like:

https://github.com/openstack/ironic/blob/master/ironic/common/states.py#L181"}, {'account_id': 1297, 'date': '2015-07-07 00:34:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

recheck'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-07-07 01:26:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified+1

- gate-automaton-pep8 http://logs.openstack.org/15/197815/3/check/gate-automaton-pep8/39ffc5f/ : SUCCESS in 54s
- gate-automaton-docs http://docs-draft.openstack.org/15/197815/3/check/gate-automaton-docs/b40bcb6//doc/build/html/ : SUCCESS in 44s
- gate-automaton-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/15/197815/3/check/gate-automaton-python27/685ddbe/ : SUCCESS in 2m 06s
- gate-automaton-python34 http://logs.openstack.org/15/197815/3/check/gate-automaton-python34/dda96f0/ : SUCCESS in 42s
- gate-tempest-dsvm-neutron-src-automaton http://logs.openstack.org/15/197815/3/check/gate-tempest-dsvm-neutron-src-automaton/62c6a3d/ : SUCCESS in 51m 52s'}, {'account_id': 6601, 'date': '2015-07-07 15:16:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

I like the label solution better than the dictionary, since it allows labels to be used everywhere, which hopefully reduces some confusion.

I was looking at the logs like this one: 

https://github.com/openstack/automaton/blob/master/automaton/machines.py#L103

but the example in ironic is a good consumer example.'}, {'account_id': 1297, 'date': '2015-07-08 20:21:53.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Hmmm, ya though I wonder if we should just skip the label stuff, and just recommend people use states that don't format badly/aka look like crap. Because a lot of the other callbacks and such get the state name, and to provide the label also (just so people can use a human-readable label) seems overly complicated, they could/should just use the 'human-readable label' as the state in the first place (IMHO)... So meh, idk, having this dictionary seems ok, to have different names on conversion; but using it through-out the state machine, idk."}, {'account_id': 6601, 'date': '2015-07-08 21:48:44.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Good point, really don't want to have to pass two things.

I think I might be confused about the use case for adding this.   I was thinking this was something I'd use to aid in debugging, so I'd want to be able to map what was in the logs to what was used in the pydot graph.

Is this instead to have more readable names when this is being shown to a user as documentation?

Hmm, I guess for my use case, I could run this twice once with and again without to get the mapping ... maybe add an option to show both.  That is, pydot would use 'Label' by default (if dict specified) but with the new option it would use 'Label(icky_thing)' when they differ."}, {'account_id': 1297, 'date': '2015-07-09 18:21:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Hmmm, thats possible.'}, {'account_id': 10584, 'date': '2015-07-09 22:16:24.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Seems like it would be simpler to disallow passing in None as a state, and throw an exception if a None state is passed.  A 'None' string is fine, but a python None seems like they're neglecting to provide a state, which is undefined.  Each state in a fsm should be defined and distinct, an 'undefined' or 'None' state is still defined, the string is the definition of what the state is."}, {'account_id': 1297, 'date': '2015-07-09 23:32:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Ya so there is also that possiblity.'}, {'account_id': 1297, 'date': '2015-07-09 23:33:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Which I'd be fine with, non-none states imho make sense (if people can't figure out a useful name or string or something for there states and resort to none they might want to think it over a little)."}, {'account_id': 10584, 'date': '2015-07-30 16:41:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 5638, 'date': '2015-07-30 19:40:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-07-30 19:40:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: -Verified

commit_message:
Allow providing a state-name translation dict

Certain projects use ``None`` as a state (and it is
possible for other projects to use other hashable
objects as states) so make it possible to provide
a renaming dict that can provide an alternative name
mapping.

This allows those projects to translate their states
into something useful on conversion.

Change-Id: I1debeaf0c1d7a7af58376ada50b014cf5de40746

commit_message:
Add ironic-inspector to project list for python-ironic-inspector-client

Looks like otherwise Zuul cloner does not catch and clone it.
Instead, devstack tries to do a direct clone and fails with
"Cloning not allowed in this configuration".

Change-Id: I722e21ddeb76e3f4034141a05788c15599553cf6

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC
    Workflow: http://docs.openstack.org/infra/manual/developers.html
    Commit Messages: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/GitCommitMessages"}, {'account_id': 6547, 'date': '2015-07-20 03:41:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

This seems to be a duplicate of https://review.openstack.org/#/c/202790/ - can't you please abandon one of them?

As commented on the other change, the existing cinder behaviour matches many command line tools - rm, 'git rm', mv, etc - they print nothing unnecessary during success, just return an exit status of 0. 

Any change such as this one risks breaking scripts and there is no justification for the change. I think the response to the bug should be 'by design'. Are there any other openstack clients that are more verbose?"}, {'account_id': 16197, 'date': '2015-07-21 06:03:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Thanks Duncan Thomas for the review comments.

1. I abandoned the duplicate one and this will be the one for reviewing.

2. Are there any other openstack clients that are more verbose?.
Yes, The last version of all openstack client will give a response message whether it success or error. Below are the list...

The success response message is very helpful we deleting 100 volumes in loop or in list....

eg:

nova delete <VM_ID>
Request to delete server <VM_ID> has been accepted.


nova delete <VM_ID_1> <VM_ID_2> <VM_ID_3>
Request to delete server <VM_ID_1> has been accepted.
Request to delete server <VM_ID_2> has been accepted.
Request to delete server <VM_ID_3> has been accepted.

Similarly for swift

swift delete test <object_name>
<object_name>



Please review my comments and let me know your comments...'}, {'account_id': 16197, 'date': '2015-07-21 06:03:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 1207, 'date': '2015-07-22 07:59:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

commit_message:
Add response message when volume delete

When a request is send for deleting a volume it will not print any
success message if it deleted successfully.It will print only error
message if the volume deletion fails. This fix will print response
message if the volume deletion is success.

Change-Id: Icef2045107e1dcc3b7f2abfeb50b3f180ded1a27
Closes-Bug: #1475430

commit_message:
Move gate-ironic-inspector-dsvm to (non-voting) check pipeline of ironic

The job proved working in experimental pipeline, e.g.:
http://logs.openstack.org/22/194722/6/experimental/check-ironic-inspector-dsvm-nv/9ed2a9c/
(expected success) or
http://logs.openstack.org/44/202544/1/experimental/gate-ironic-inspector-dsvm-nv/1c1e49f/
(expected failure).

Now we can let it run on all changes (still non-voting).

Change-Id: I3926c42d1b4bdc36ee0fd93475454bc5a051597b

Add switch to disable predefined networks

* neutron_settings['create_predefined_networks'] = true/false
* default = true

Change-Id: I633b01214e0c1467b5dadb480948ed51134ef55d
Closes-Bug: 1471244

messages:
[{'account_id': 17580, 'date': '2015-07-30 19:50:56.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 10068, 'date': '2015-07-30 19:51:01.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC
    Workflow: http://docs.openstack.org/infra/manual/developers.html

commit_message:
Add ceph devstack job to requirements

A regression was introduced to glance_store which affected its
use with ceph.  Ceph jobs are run for several projects, but not
requirements, therefore the regression was not noted when
glance_store was released and the requirements uppper constraint
increased.  Run the ceph job on requirements changes.

Change-Id: I61a240817616d88863318b972edadfd67ea35d6c
Related-bug: #1475811

commit_message:
Add -n to tcpdump as part of net_probe

In order to prevent tcpdump from hanging due to no available DNS
servers, we need to add -n to command line parameters.

Change-Id: I33e1472a89ee6d0ca9ee2d0f9dbd4871ad6e3817
Closes-Bug: 1466020

commit_message:
Memcache and Haproxy fixes for keystone

* Set [cache]memcache_dead_retry and [memcache]dead_retry
  to 300
* Change check in haproxy for keystone to rise 150

Change-Id: I83d67b17d8a4d74b87e47bccfe6347edb33862ad
Closes-Bug: #1471318

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

commit_message:
Collect constraints

Common constraints like ISO_8601 should be collect in one common
path. Other client constraints should be separate from
other resources (like plugin) and put in the common directory as well if that
constraint did not use client at all.

blueprint collect-constraints

Change-Id: I4193884484ae25ff4f6331cf825ae501c8c11d6b

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-07-28 10:50:06.000000000', 'message': 'Fix test_migrations on Python 3

migrate.versioning.api.VerNum() conversion to integer doesn't work in
all cases. Cast explicitly to int in WalkVersionsMixin.walk_versions()
to fix this issue.

Modify unit tests to use VerNum objects instead of using directly
integers. The bug was not seen in tests because tests used int numbers.

Example of error:

    Traceback (most recent call last):
      ...
      File "oslo_db/sqlalchemy/test_migrations.py", line 189, in walk_versions
        versions = range(self.INIT_VERSION + 1, self.REPOSITORY.latest + 1)
    TypeError: 'VerNum' object cannot be interpreted as an integer

This bug impact for example glance.tests.unit.test_migrations of the
Glance project.

Change-Id: I043a66268b957b97f2e8f652c0ee8aec3a00e8dd
'}]
commit_message:
Fix test_migrations on Python 3

migrate.versioning.api.VerNum() conversion to integer doesn't work in
all cases. Cast explicitly to int in WalkVersionsMixin.walk_versions()
to fix this issue.

Modify unit tests to use VerNum objects instead of using directly
integers. The bug was not seen in tests because tests used int numbers.

Example of error:

    Traceback (most recent call last):
      ...
      File "oslo_db/sqlalchemy/test_migrations.py", line 189, in walk_versions
        versions = range(self.INIT_VERSION + 1, self.REPOSITORY.latest + 1)
    TypeError: 'VerNum' object cannot be interpreted as an integer

This bug impact for example glance.tests.unit.test_migrations of the
Glance project.

Change-Id: I043a66268b957b97f2e8f652c0ee8aec3a00e8dd

commit_message:
Access volume groups created by Cinder from the host

Cinder creates volume groups that can't be seen from the host unless
/etc/lvm is mounted into the data container.  When /etc/lvm is mounted,
the host is able to see the volumes Cinder creates, and delete
them when needed.  Also, Cinder volumes remain persistant while follow
container best practices.

Change-Id: I01ad0a20fe1ae7317069b3b567d18bba590b0a31
Closes-bug: #1460134

commit_message:
VMware: clean up exceptions

The driver should not raise a Vim exception but rather a known
nova exception.

In addition to this it removes an invalid comment.

TrivialFix

commit_message:
Fix some time related function calls

We should use the timeutils module from oslo_utils when possible.

Change-Id: Ie5bbd5898dc084e6af311153f45c2b67fcd92a43
